'''Edward Christopher Sheeran''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MBE}} ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|ʃ|ɪər|ən}} {{respell|SHEER|ən}}; born 17 February 1991) is an English singer-songwriter. Born in [[Halifax, West Yorkshire]], and raised in [[Framlingham, Suffolk]], he began writing songs around the age of eleven. In early 2011, Sheeran independently released the extended play ''[[No. 5 Collaborations Project]]''. He signed with [[Asylum Records]] the same year.

Sheeran's debut album, ''[[+ (album)|+]]'' ("''Plus''"), was released in September 2011 and topped the [[UK Albums Chart]]. It contained his first hit single "[[The A Team (Ed Sheeran song)|The A Team]]". In 2012, Sheeran won the [[Brit Awards]] for [[Brit Award for British Male Solo Artist|Best British Male Solo Artist]] and [[Brit Award for British Breakthrough Act|British Breakthrough Act]]. Sheeran's second studio album, ''[[x (Ed Sheeran album)|×]]'' ("''Multiply''"), topped charts around the world upon its release in June 2014. It was named the second-best-selling album worldwide of 2015. In the same year, ''×'' won [[Brit Awards 2015#Nominees and winners|Album of the Year]] at the [[2015 Brit Awards]], and he received the [[Ivor Novello Awards|Ivor Novello Award]] for Songwriter of the Year from the [[British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors]]. A single from ''×'', "[[Thinking Out Loud]]", earned him the 2016 [[Grammy Award]]s for [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]].

Sheeran's third album, ''[[÷ (album)|÷]]'' ("''Divide''"), was released in March 2017, and was the [[List of best-selling albums#Best-selling album by year worldwide|best-selling album worldwide of 2017]]. The first two singles from the album, "[[Shape of You]]" and "[[Castle on the Hill]]", broke records in a number of countries by debuting in the top two positions of the charts. He also became the first artist to have two songs debut in the US top 10 in the same week. By March 2017, Sheeran had accumulated ten top-10 singles from ''÷'' on the [[UK Singles Chart]], breaking the record for most top-10 UK singles from one album. His fourth single from ''÷'', "[[Perfect (Ed Sheeran song)|Perfect]]", reached number one in the US, Australia, and the UK, where it became the [[List of UK Singles Chart Christmas number ones|Christmas number one]] in 2017. The world's best-selling artist of 2017, he was named the [[Global Recording Artist of the Year]]. Released in 2019, his fourth overall and first collaborative album, ''[[No.6 Collaborations Project]]'', debuted at number one in most major markets, and spawned three UK number one singles, "[[I Don't Care (Ed Sheeran and Justin Bieber song)|I Don't Care]]", "[[Beautiful People (Ed Sheeran song)|Beautiful People]]", and "[[Take Me Back to London]]". His fifth studio album, ''[[= (album)|=]]'' ("''Equals''"), topped the charts in most major markets in 2021. His sixth album, ''[[- (album)|-]]'' ("''Subtract''"), was released on 5 May 2023, while his seventh album, ''[[Autumn Variations]]'', was released on 29 September 2023 under his own record label, Gingerbread Man Records.

Sheeran has sold more than 150 million records worldwide, making him one of the [[List of best-selling music artists|world's best-selling music artists]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/solo-party-ed-sheeran-releases-album-while-isolating-covid-2021-10-29/|title='Solo party': Ed Sheeran releases album while isolating for COVID|work=[[Reuters]]|date=29 October 2021|access-date=29 October 2021|archive-date=16 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220816094522/https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/solo-party-ed-sheeran-releases-album-while-isolating-covid-2021-10-29/|url-status=live}}</ref> He has 101 million [[RIAA]]-certified units in the US,<ref>{{cite news |title=Gold & Platinum |website=[[RIAA]] |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/ |access-date=29 June 2020 |archive-date=12 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212231947/https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and two of his albums are in the list of the [[List of best-selling albums in the United Kingdom|best-selling albums in UK chart history]]. In December 2019, the [[Official Charts Company]] named him artist of the decade, with the most combined success in the UK album and singles charts in the 2010s.<ref name="Decade">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-50732153 |title=Ed Sheeran named 'artist of the decade' |date=11 December 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=11 December 2019 |archive-date=11 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211082444/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-50732153 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of July 2024, he is the 3rd most followed artist on [[Spotify]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://volt.fm/most-followed-artists|title=Most followers on Spotify|date=29 July 2024|website=volt.fm|access-date=29 July 2024}}</ref> Beginning in March 2017, his [[÷ Tour]] became the [[List of highest-grossing concert tours|highest-grossing of all time]] in August 2019. An alumnus of the [[National Youth Theatre]] in London, Sheeran's acting roles include appearing in the 2019 film ''[[Yesterday (2019 film)|Yesterday]]'', playing himself.

== Early life and education ==
[[File:Franglingham Castle 01.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|[[Framlingham Castle]] in Sheeran's home town. The castle and his upbringing in Framlingham is the subject of his 2017 single "[[Castle on the Hill]]".<ref>{{cite web|last=Adejobi|first=Alicia|title=Inside the real Castle On The Hill where Ed Sheeran 'found love' and 'got drunk'|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/inside-real-castle-hill-where-ed-sheeran-found-love-got-drunk-1600101|website=International Business Times UK|access-date=11 January 2017|date=9 January 2017|archive-date=13 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113133637/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/inside-real-castle-hill-where-ed-sheeran-found-love-got-drunk-1600101|url-status=live}}</ref>]]
Edward Christopher Sheeran was born on 17 February 1991 in [[Halifax, West Yorkshire]], England.<ref name=allmusicbio>{{cite web| url = https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ed-sheeran-mn0002639628/biography| title = Ed Sheeran Biography| first = Jon| last = O'Brien| website = [[AllMusic]]| access-date = 10 December 2015| archive-date = 26 May 2019| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190526141635/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ed-sheeran-mn0002639628/biography| url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hebdenbridgetimes.co.uk/whats-on/music/halifax-born-singer-ed-sheeran-wins-top-award-1-7001208|title=Halifax-born singer Ed Sheeran wins top award|date=12 December 2014|work=The Hebden Bridge Times|access-date=16 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317143550/http://www.hebdenbridgetimes.co.uk/whats-on/music/halifax-born-singer-ed-sheeran-wins-top-award-1-7001208|archive-date=17 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> His early childhood home was on Birchcliffe Road in nearby [[Hebden Bridge]].<ref name=earlyhome>{{cite web | url = https://www.elmetfarmhouse.co.uk/10-fascinating-facts-about-funky-hebden-bridge/ | title = 10 Fascinating Facts about Funky Hebden Bridge | access-date = 25 February 2019 | first = Lesley | last = Jackson | date = 22 February 2016 | work = Elmet Farmhouse | quote = World-famous singer songwriter Ed Sheeran spent his formative early childhood years in Hebden Bridge and seems to have absorbed its quirky, independent spirit. | archive-date = 25 February 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200225071845/https://www.elmetfarmhouse.co.uk/10-fascinating-facts-about-funky-hebden-bridge/ | url-status = live }}</ref> His father was a curator at [[Cartwright Hall]] in [[Bradford]], and his mother worked at [[Manchester City Art Gallery]].<ref name=earlyhome/><ref>{{Cite news |last=Russell |first=Sam |date=29 September 2022 |title=Ed Sheeran's father shares details of his life in art in speech at charity event |language=en-GB |work=Belfast Telegraph |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/music/news/ed-sheerans-father-shares-details-of-his-life-in-art-in-speech-at-charity-event/42026078.html |access-date=26 November 2023 |issn=0307-1235 |archive-date=26 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231126100650/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/music/news/ed-sheerans-father-shares-details-of-his-life-in-art-in-speech-at-charity-event/42026078.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=29 September 2022 |title=Ed Sheeran's father shares details of his life in art in speech at charity event |url=https://www.irishnews.com/magazine/entertainment/2022/09/29/news/ed_sheeran_s_father_shares_details_of_his_life_in_art_in_speech_at_charity_event-2843968/ |access-date=16 November 2023 |website=The Irish News |language=en |archive-date=26 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231126095544/https://www.irishnews.com/magazine/entertainment/2022/09/29/news/ed_sheeran_s_father_shares_details_of_his_life_in_art_in_speech_at_charity_event-2843968/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 1995, he moved with his family from Hebden Bridge to [[Framlingham]] in [[Suffolk]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Sean |title=Sheeran: A Biography |date=2019 |publisher=Diversion Books}}</ref><ref name="TheInd-Walsh">{{cite news|last=Walsh|first=John|date=6 December 2014|title=Ed Sheeran: Boy next door who made it very big|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/ed-sheeran-boy-next-door-who-made-it-very-big-9907243.html|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=8 November 2015|archive-date=15 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115160407/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/ed-sheeran-boy-next-door-who-made-it-very-big-9907243.html|url-status=live}}</ref> where he attended the independent [[Brandeston Hall]] [[Preparatory school (United Kingdom)|preparatory school]] (now [[Framlingham College]] Prep School),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/ed-sheeran-new-album-divide|title=How Ed Sheeran became the biggest male popstar on the planet|date=2 February 2017|website=British GQ|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=24 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220124024832/https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/ed-sheeran-new-album-divide|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldframlinghamian.com/article.php?story=20170124172421166|title=Ed Sheeran meets best mate from Brandeston Hall on Graham Norton Show - OldFramlinghamian.com|website=oldframlinghamian.com|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=25 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211025214229/http://www.oldframlinghamian.com/article.php?story=20170124172421166|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.framlinghamcollege.co.uk/cocurricular/music/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200814111116/https://www.framlinghamcollege.co.uk/cocurricular/music/|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 August 2020|title=Music|date=14 August 2020}}</ref> then [[Thomas Mills High School]], also in Framlingham.<ref name="auto">{{cite news |author=Rock and Pop Features |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/8679492/Ed-Sheeran-I-havent-got-used-to-the-screams.html |title=Ed Sheeran: 'I haven't got used to the screams' |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=3 August 2011 |access-date=8 June 2013 |location=London |archive-date=17 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617211441/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/8679492/Ed-Sheeran-I-havent-got-used-to-the-screams.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="intro">{{cite web | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/suffolk/content/articles/2008/04/22/introducing_ed_sheeran_feature.shtml | title = Introducing – Ed Sheeran | publisher = [[BBC Suffolk]] | access-date = 11 August 2011 | date = April 2008 | archive-date = 11 January 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180111084619/http://www.bbc.co.uk/suffolk/content/articles/2008/04/22/introducing_ed_sheeran_feature.shtml | url-status = live }}</ref> He has an older brother named Matthew, who works as a composer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chart Beat Podcast: Matt Sheeran on Working With Brother Ed, & Andrea Bocelli, on 'Perfect' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/podcasts/8097573/matt-sheeran-ed-sheeran-andrea-bocelli-perfect-chart-beat-podcast |access-date=26 September 2018 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=21 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211021215353/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/podcasts/8097573/matt-sheeran-ed-sheeran-andrea-bocelli-perfect-chart-beat-podcast |url-status=live }}</ref> Sheeran's parents, John and Imogen, are from London. His father is Irish,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wjlondon.com/athurs-day-ed-sheeran-interview/|title=Arthur's Day: Ed Sheeran interview -|date=21 September 2011|access-date=7 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802044151/http://wjlondon.com/athurs-day-ed-sheeran-interview/|archive-date=2 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{sfn|Nolan|2012|pp=1–6}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/ed-sheeran-irish-blood-english-heart-26779193.html|title=Ed Sheeran: Irish blood, English heart|last=Welch|first=Andy|date=10 June 2011|website=[[Irish Independent]]|access-date=8 November 2015|archive-date=15 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615032300/https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/ed-sheeran-irish-blood-english-heart-26779193.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and Sheeran has stated that his father is from a "very large" [[Irish Catholic|Catholic]] family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://965tic.cbslocal.com/2013/08/06/qa-with-ed-sheeran-at-the-acoustic-cafe/|title=Q&A With Ed Sheeran at the Acoustic Café|last=Roman|first=Tyler|date=6 August 2013|website=Cbslocal.com|access-date=8 November 2015|archive-date=19 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119083438/http://965tic.cbslocal.com/2013/08/06/qa-with-ed-sheeran-at-the-acoustic-cafe/|url-status=live}}</ref> John is an art curator and lecturer, and Imogen is a culture publicist turned jewellery designer.{{sfn|Nolan|2012|pp=1–6}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Sage|first=Sarky|date=31 March 2011|title=Framlingham: Pop star Ed Sheeran's mum has success with jewellery range – News – East Anglian Daily Times|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/framlingham_pop_star_ed_sheeran_s_mum_has_success_with_jewellery_range_1_844578|newspaper=[[East Anglian Daily Times]]|access-date=8 November 2015|archive-date=3 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303175505/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/framlingham_pop_star_ed_sheeran_s_mum_has_success_with_jewellery_range_1_844578|url-status=live}}</ref> His parents ran Sheeran Lock, an independent art consultancy, from 1990 to 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suffolkmag.co.uk/people/celebrity-interviews/the_man_who_loves_art_1_3608139|title=The man who loves art|last=Larner|first=Catherine|date=20 May 2014|publisher=Suffolkmag.co.uk|access-date=9 November 2015|archive-date=17 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317074414/http://www.suffolkmag.co.uk/people/celebrity-interviews/the_man_who_loves_art_1_3608139|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Sheeran sang at a local church choir at the age of four, learned how to play the guitar at age eleven,<ref name="Clapton"/> and began writing songs while at Thomas Mills High School in Framlingham.<ref name="auto"/><ref name="intro"/> He also played the cello when he was younger.<ref name="ClassicFM-2022-01-23">{{cite web |last=Alexandra |first=Sophia |url=https://www.classicfm.com/music-news/ed-sheeran-yo-yo-ma/ |title=Ed Sheeran: 'Yo-Yo Ma emailed me to tell me he loved my song Shape of You' |publisher=[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]] |place=London |date=23 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220123084549/https://www.classicfm.com/music-news/ed-sheeran-yo-yo-ma/ |accessdate=26 August 2022 |archive-date=23 January 2022 |url-status=live }}</ref> A 2004 school report described him as a "natural performer", and his classmates also voted him "most likely to be famous".<ref name="Exhibition">{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran exhibition in Ipswich features college drop-out letter |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-49398768 |date=19 August 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=19 August 2019 |archive-date=12 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211212010225/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-49398768 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was accepted at the [[National Youth Theatre]] in London as a teenager.<ref>{{cite web |first=Richard |last=Haugh |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/suffolk/content/articles/2008/04/22/introducing_ed_sheeran_feature.shtml |title=Suffolk – Entertainment – Ed Sheeran |publisher=BBC |date=22 April 2008 |access-date=8 June 2013 |archive-date=11 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111084619/http://www.bbc.co.uk/suffolk/content/articles/2008/04/22/introducing_ed_sheeran_feature.shtml |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scoutlondon.com/2013/02/01/ed-sheeran-i-want-a-couple-of-months-off/ |title=Ed Sheeran: 'I want a couple of months off' &#124; Scout London > Music |publisher=Scout London |date=1 February 2013 |access-date=8 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225022922/http://www.scoutlondon.com/2013/02/01/ed-sheeran-i-want-a-couple-of-months-off/ |archive-date=25 February 2014 }}</ref> He successfully auditioned for [[Youth Music Theatre UK]] in 2007 and joined their production of ''[[Frankenstein – A New Musical]]'' in [[Plymouth]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://britishyouthmusictheatre.org/shows/frankenstein-2007 |title=Frankenstein (2007). Barbican Theatre, Plymouth, Cast |website=[[British Youth Music Theatre]] |access-date=20 December 2018 |archive-date=21 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211021215029/https://britishyouthmusictheatre.org/shows/frankenstein-2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> He is a patron of Youth Music Theatre UK (now renamed British Youth Music Theatre)<ref name="Patron">{{cite web|date=28 January 2013 |title=Sheeran penned 26 new album tracks |url=http://music.uk.msn.com/news/sheeran-penned-26-new-album-tracks|work=MSN Music |publisher=[[MSN]] |access-date=12 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130130160724/http://music.uk.msn.com/news/sheeran-penned-26-new-album-tracks|archive-date=30 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and of [[Access to Music]], where he studied Artist Development.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patron Ed Sheeran|url=http://www.accesstomusic.co.uk/patron_ed-sheeran-7|website=Access to Music|access-date=12 August 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003105903/http://www.accesstomusic.co.uk/patron_ed-sheeran-7|archive-date=3 October 2015}}</ref><ref name="Access to Music">{{cite web|title=Student Success Stories|url=http://www.accesstomusic.co.uk/success-stories|website=Access to Music|access-date=12 August 2015|archive-date=1 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901233818/http://www.accesstomusic.co.uk/success-stories|url-status=live}}</ref> Sheeran is a [[second cousin]] of Northern Irish broadcaster [[Gordon Burns]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/film-and-tv/gordon-burns-so-proud-over-682724 |title=Gordon Burns 'so proud' over cousin Ed Sheeran's Brit Awards success |work=Manchester Evening News |date=23 February 2012 |access-date=7 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028040821/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/film-and-tv/gordon-burns-so-proud-over-682724 |archive-date=28 October 2014 }}</ref> who hosted the British game show ''[[The Krypton Factor]]''.{{sfn|Nolan|2012|pp=1–6}}

==Career==
===2004–2010: Career beginnings===
[[File:12 - Ed Sheeran.jpg|thumb|right|160px|Sheeran performing at the Ipswich Arts Festival in July 2010]]

Sheeran began recording music in 2004, and at the age of thirteen independently released his first collection of work, titled ''Spinning Man''.{{efn|group=upper-alpha|"In 2004, I made my very first album, ''Spinning Man'', named after a picture that my dad had. I burnt the CDs myself and made the covers. There were 14 songs and they were all songs that rhymed. One lyric went: '''I'm a typical average teen, if you know what I mean.''' There are probably 20 copies of ''Spinning Man'' in existence and I have 19 of them. I don't want anyone else to get hold of a copy. Most of the songs were about a girl named Claire. She was my first love when I was 13. It was a very innocent love and we only ever held hands, but it lasted a fair amount of time. Then came my first devastating break-up. Looking back, it really wasn't that bad, but at the time it was soul-shattering. When she left me, I wrote a lot of songs off the back of it—my first love songs."<ref>''Ed Sheeran: A Visual Journey'', p.&nbsp;38</ref>}} He has been friends with fellow English singer [[Passenger (singer)|Passenger]] since he was 15, with the two playing the same gig in Cambridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/music/2012/12/07/passenger_aka_mike_rosenberg_grateful_for_ed_sheerans_support.html|title=Passenger, a.k.a. Mike Rosenberg, grateful for Ed Sheeran's support|work=Toronto Star|date=7 December 2012|access-date=28 September 2014|archive-date=5 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905175122/https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/music/2012/12/07/passenger_aka_mike_rosenberg_grateful_for_ed_sheerans_support.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He moved to London in 2008 and began playing in small venues. In 2008, he auditioned for the ITV series ''[[Britannia High]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/edinburgh-evening-news/edinburgh/interview-ed-sheeran-musician-1-2039807|title=Interview: Ed Sheeran, musician|date=5 January 2012|work=Edinburgh Evening News|access-date=23 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407085515/http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/what-s-on/music/interview-ed-sheeran-musician-1-2039807|archive-date=7 April 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> He also opened for [[Nizlopi]] in Norwich in April 2008, after being one of their guitar technicians.<ref name="intro"/> In the autumn of 2009, Sheeran began studying music at the [[Academy of Contemporary Music]] (ACM) in [[Guildford]], Surrey as an undergraduate at the age of 18,<ref name=acm1>{{cite web|url=http://www.acm.ac.uk/ed-sheeran-musician-and-songwriter/|title=Featured Alumni: Ed Sheeran – Musician/Songwriter|date=6 October 2015|access-date=8 November 2016|archive-date=29 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729224303/https://www.acm.ac.uk/ed-sheeran-musician-and-songwriter/|url-status=live}}</ref> but left without permission in the same year to support hip-hop artist [[Just Jack]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/ed-sheeran-donates-200k-boosts-22900266|title=Ed Sheeran donates £200k and boosts results at old school where he met wife Cherry|date=24 October 2020|work=Mirror|access-date=13 November 2012|archive-date=16 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220816094521/https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/ed-sheeran-donates-200k-boosts-22900266|url-status=live}}</ref>
He released another EP in 2009, ''You Need Me'', and also collaborated several times with Essex singer [[Leddra Chapman]], including [[CeeLo Green]]'s "[[Fuck You (CeeLo Green song)|Fuck You]]". In February 2010, Sheeran posted a video through [[SB.TV]]—a channel launched by British entrepreneur [[Jamal Edwards]]—and rapper [[Example (musician)|Example]] invited Sheeran to tour with him.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jamal Edwards, music entrepreneur and YouTube star, dies aged 31 |url=https://news.sky.com/story/jamal-edwards-music-entrepreneur-and-youtube-star-dies-aged-31-12547675 |access-date=21 February 2022 |work=[[Sky News]] |archive-date=20 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220220234057/https://news.sky.com/story/jamal-edwards-music-entrepreneur-and-youtube-star-dies-aged-31-12547675 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the same month, he also released his critically acclaimed ''[[Loose Change (EP)|Loose Change]]'' EP, which featured his future debut single, "[[The A Team (Ed Sheeran song)|The A Team]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soulsidefunk.com/2010/03/12/interview-with-ed-sheeran/ |title=Interview with Ed Sheeran |date=12 March 2010 |website=Soulside funk |access-date=30 November 2014 |archive-date=29 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629102811/https://soulsidefunk.com/2010/03/12/interview-with-ed-sheeran/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Sheeran began to be seen by more people over the internet through YouTube and his fan base expanded, with him also receiving praise from ''[[The Independent]]'' newspaper and [[Elton John]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Singer Ed Sheeran: 'Elton John is a fan of my music' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/entertainment-arts-14718488/singer-ed-sheeran-elton-john-is-a-fan-of-my-music |work=[[BBC News]] |date=3 January 2019 |access-date=27 August 2022 |archive-date=23 May 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200523234601/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/entertainment-arts-14718488/singer-ed-sheeran-elton-john-is-a-fan-of-my-music |url-status=live }}</ref> He played a ''Station Session'' in [[St Pancras railway station|St. Pancras International]] in June 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DKEkAf4EYCA|title=The Station Sessions: Ed Sheeran (10 June 2010)|date=6 May 2017 |access-date=3 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816212256/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DKEkAf4EYCA|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status=live|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/radio/q/blog/watch-ed-sheeran-play-in-a-london-train-station-before-he-was-famous-1.4200070 | title=Watch Ed Sheeran play in a London train station before he was famous – Blog | work=[[Q (radio show)|q]] | publisher=[[CBC Radio]] | access-date=13 September 2017 | author=Van Evra, Jennifer | archive-date=15 August 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815134842/http://www.cbc.ca/radio/q/blog/watch-ed-sheeran-play-in-a-london-train-station-before-he-was-famous-1.4200070 | url-status=live }}</ref> Some of the episode is on their Facebook page<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/StationSessions/videos/103760926340944/|title=Ed Sheeran – The Station Sessions – 10th June 2010|via=facebook.com|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=8 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220408153746/https://www.facebook.com/StationSessions/videos/103760926340944/|url-status=live}}</ref> Sheeran also self-released two other EPs in 2010, ''Ed Sheeran: Live at the Bedford'' and ''[[Songs I Wrote with Amy]]'', which is a collection of love songs he wrote in Wales with [[Amy Wadge]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/ed-sheeran-thinking-out-loud-7345585|title=How I wrote Ed Sheeran's song... on Harry Styles' guitar|last=Price|first=Karen|date=30 June 2014|work=walesonline|access-date=17 October 2018|archive-date=27 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827174126/https://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/ed-sheeran-thinking-out-loud-7345585|url-status=live}}</ref> When in Los Angeles in 2010, he was invited to perform at The Foxxhole, a club run by actor [[Jamie Foxx]], which ended with an invitation to stay at Foxx's home.<ref name="Telegraph 2017">{{cite news|title=Ed Sheeran: 'I haven't got used to the screams'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/8679492/Ed-Sheeran-I-havent-got-used-to-the-screams.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=12 December 2017|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=17 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617211441/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/8679492/Ed-Sheeran-I-havent-got-used-to-the-screams.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 8 January 2011, Sheeran released another independent EP, ''[[No. 5 Collaborations Project]]'', featuring grime artists such as [[Wiley (rapper)|Wiley]], [[Jme (MC)|Jme]], [[Devlin (rapper)|Devlin]], [[Sway (British musician)|Sway]] and [[Ghetts]].<ref name=bbcsuffolk>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/suffolk/hi/people_and_places/music/newsid_9354000/9354954.stm|work=BBC News|access-date=10 August 2011|date=10 January 2011|title=Ed Sheeran battles Rihanna for top spot in album chart|first=Richard|last=Haugh|archive-date=14 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114061930/http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/suffolk/hi/people_and_places/music/newsid_9354000/9354954.stm|url-status=live}}</ref> With this EP, Sheeran gained mainstream attention for having reached number 2 in the [[iTunes]] chart without any promotion or label, selling over 7,000 copies in the first week.<ref name=signing>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/suffolk/hi/people_and_places/music/newsid_9354000/9354954.stm |title=Ed Sheeran signs with Asylum Records / Atlantic Records following 'No. 5 Collaborations Project' success |work=BBC News |date=13 January 2011 |access-date=19 January 2011 |archive-date=14 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114061930/http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/suffolk/hi/people_and_places/music/newsid_9354000/9354954.stm |url-status=live }}</ref> Three months later, Sheeran put on a free show to fans at the Barfly in [[Camden Town]]. Over 1,000 fans turned up, so Sheeran played four different shows to ensure everyone saw a gig, including a gig outside on the street after the venue had closed. Later that month, Sheeran was signed to [[Asylum Records]].<ref name=signing/>

===2011–2013: ''+'' ("''Plus''")===
On 26 April 2011, Sheeran appeared on the BBC music show ''[[Later... with Jools Holland]]'', where he performed his debut single "The A Team". Six weeks later, "The A Team" was released as a digital download in the UK. The release served as the lead single from Sheeran's debut studio album, ''[[+ (album)|+]]'' ("Plus").<ref>{{cite news|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|title=Ed Sheeran, 'x': Track-By-Track Review|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/review/6128781/ed-sheeran-x-track-by-track-album-review|issue=24 November 2015|magazine=Billboard|date=23 June 2014|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=16 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210516000257/https://www.billboard.com/articles/review/6128781/ed-sheeran-x-track-by-track-album-review|url-status=live}}</ref> "The A Team" entered the [[UK Singles Chart]] at number three, selling over 58,000 copies in the first week. It was the best-selling debut single and the overall eighth-best selling single of 2011, selling 801,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-top-20-biggest-selling-singles-of-2011-revealed/ |title=The Top 20 biggest selling singles of 2011 revealed! |publisher=Officialcharts.com |access-date=8 June 2013 |archive-date=20 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620014158/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-top-20-biggest-selling-singles-of-2011-revealed/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The lead single also became a top ten hit in Australia, Germany, Ireland, Japan, Luxembourg, New Zealand, Norway and the Netherlands. During a headline set in the [[BBC Introducing]] tent at [[Glastonbury Festival 2011]], Sheeran announced that "[[You Need Me, I Don't Need You]]" would be released on 26 August as the second single from the album. The second single peaked at number four on the UK Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20110904/7501/ |title=2011-09-10 Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |date=10 September 2011 |access-date=8 June 2013 |archive-date=24 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624032544/http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20110904/7501/ |url-status=live }}</ref> "[[Lego House]]" was released as the third single, reaching the top ten on the Australian, Irish and New Zealand Singles Charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/lego-house-ep/id474197789|title=Lego House – EP by Ed Sheeran on Apple Music|date=11 November 2011|publisher=iTunes Store|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=5 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305075953/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/lego-house-ep/id474197789|url-status=live}}</ref> The music video for "Lego House" features actor [[Rupert Grint]], as a play on their similar appearance.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=5 times Rupert Grint and Ed Sheeran joked about being the same person |url=https://ew.com/music/2017/03/22/rupert-grint-ed-sheeran-moments/ |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=8 May 2018 |access-date=27 August 2022 |archive-date=8 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220408153746/https://ew.com/music/2017/03/22/rupert-grint-ed-sheeran-moments/ |url-status=live }}</ref> "[[Drunk (Ed Sheeran song)|Drunk]]", released on 19 February 2012, became Sheeran's fourth consecutive top-ten single in the UK, peaking at number nine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20120304/7501/ |title=2012-03-10 Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |date=10 March 2012 |access-date=8 June 2013 |archive-date=26 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526213417/http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20120304/7501 |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[File:Ed Sheeran at 2012 Frequency Festival in Austria (7852625324).jpg|thumb|left|Sheeran at the [[FM4 Frequency Festival|Frequency Festival]] in Austria, August 2012]]
Sheeran released ''+'' on 12 September 2011. The album received generally favourable reviews from music critics<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/+/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for + |website=Metacritic |access-date=8 June 2013 |archive-date=24 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724072157/http://www.metacritic.com/music/+/critic-reviews |url-status=live }}</ref> and debuted at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]] for sales of 102,000 copies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a340995/ed-sheeran-tops-uk-album-chart-with-.html|title=Ed Sheeran tops UK album chart with '+'|last=Sperling|first=Daniel|date=18 September 2011|work=Digital Spy|access-date=23 May 2012|archive-date=27 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127024410/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a340995/ed-sheeran-tops-uk-album-chart-with-.html|url-status=live}}</ref> By end of 2011, sales of the album in the UK stood at 791,000; it became the second-best-selling debut album and the ninth-biggest-selling album there.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-top-20-biggest-selling-albums-of-2011-revealed/ |title=The Top 20 biggest selling albums of 2011 revealed! |publisher=Officialcharts.com |access-date=8 June 2013 |archive-date=28 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628051320/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-top-20-biggest-selling-albums-of-2011-revealed/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The album has been certified platinum six times by the [[British Phonographic Industry]], denoting shipments of 1.8 million copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |title=BPI Search Page by Artist |publisher=BPI |access-date=28 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625075145/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |archive-date=25 June 2014 }}</ref> As of March 2012, the album had sold 1,021,072 copies in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|first=Alan|last=Jones|title=Official Chart Analysis: Sande thrives in Scotland, Ed Sheeran album tops 1m sales in UK|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1048723&c=1|work=[[Music Week]]|access-date=6 March 2012|date=5 March 2012|archive-date=24 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724074247/http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1048723&c=1|url-status=live}}</ref> The album also reached the top five in Australia, Canada, Ireland, New Zealand and the US.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ed Sheeran Album & Song Chart History: Billboard 200|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/276089/ed+sheeran/chart?f=305|magazine=Billboard|date=15 November 2015|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=9 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709065655/http://www.billboard.com/artist/276089/ed+sheeran/chart?f=305|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fmusicvideo%2Fmusic%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=240002&arch=t&lyr=2011&year=2011&week=37 |title=GFK Chart-Track |publisher=Chart-track.co.uk |access-date=3 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724070739/http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fmusicvideo%2Fmusic%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=240002&arch=t&lyr=2011&year=2011&week=37 |archive-date=24 July 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Ed+Sheeran&titel=%2B&cat=a|title=charts.nz – Ed Sheeran – +|publisher=Hung Medien|access-date=7 March 2012|archive-date=5 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405220219/http://charts.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Ed+Sheeran&titel=%2B&cat=a|url-status=live}}</ref>

The song, "[[Moments (One Direction song)|Moments]]", on the [[Up All Night (One Direction album)|debut album]] by boy band [[One Direction]], released in November 2011, was co-written by Sheeran.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a345784/one-direction-name-debut-album-up-all-night-reveal-cover.html|title=One Direction name debut album|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=2 November 2012|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=8 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108063846/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a345784/one-direction-name-debut-album-up-all-night-reveal-cover.html|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[2012 Brit Awards]] on 21 February, Sheeran won the Brit Awards for [[Brit Award for British Male Solo Artist|Best British Male Solo Artist]], and [[Brit Award for British Breakthrough Act|British Breakthrough Act]] of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16533246|title=Brit Awards 2012: List of winners|work=[[BBC News]]|date=21 February 2012|access-date=28 September 2014|archive-date=6 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806234343/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16533246|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/adele-coldplay-lead-brit-award-nominations-20120112 |title=Adele, Coldplay Lead BRIT Award Nominations |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=12 January 2012 |access-date=28 September 2014 |archive-date=1 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701085144/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/adele-coldplay-lead-brit-award-nominations-20120112 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 10 January 2012, it was announced that Sheeran would support [[Snow Patrol]] on their US tour from late March until May.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sinchronicitymagazine.com/2012/01/ed-sheeran-announces-us-tour/ |title=Ed Sheeran Announces US Supporting Tour |publisher=Sinchronicity |date=11 January 2012 |access-date=15 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120717183352/http://sinchronicitymagazine.com/2012/01/ed-sheeran-announces-us-tour/ |archive-date=17 July 2012 }}</ref> His song, "[[Give Me Love (Ed Sheeran song)|Give Me Love]]", was featured in the episode "[[The Birthday (The Vampire Diaries)|Dangerous Liaisons]]" of ''[[The Vampire Diaries]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title='The Vampire Diaries' recap: In which Elena is starting to get on our nerves |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/02/the-vampire-diaries-recap-are-you-suggesting-i-cant-be-gentle.html |work=[[Zap2it]] |access-date=16 February 2012 |first=Carina Adly |last=MacKenzie |date=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215072514/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/02/the-vampire-diaries-recap-are-you-suggesting-i-cant-be-gentle.html |archive-date=15 February 2012 }}</ref> At the [[Ivor Novello Awards]] in May 2012, Sheeran's "The A Team" bested [[Adele]]'s "[[Rolling in the Deep]]" and [[Florence and the Machine]]'s "[[Shake It Out]]" for Best Song Musically and Lyrically.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-18107224 |title=Adele wins Ivor Novello Awards double |work=[[BBC News]] |date=17 May 2012 |access-date=17 May 2012 |archive-date=17 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517174346/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-18107224 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sheeran performed "The A Team" at the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Diamond Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II]] [[Diamond Jubilee Concert|concert]] held on [[The Mall, London|The Mall]] outside [[Buckingham Palace]] on 4 June 2012 and a cover of [[Pink Floyd]]'s "[[Wish You Were Here (Pink Floyd song)|Wish You Were Here]]" at the [[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony|closing ceremony]] of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in London on 12 August 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran Olympics Closing Ceremony: Singer Wears Hoodie, Sings Pink Floyd |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/12/ed-sheeran-olympics-closi_n_1771077.html |work=HuffPost |access-date=13 August 2012 |first=Carolyn |last=Gregoire |date=12 August 2012 |archive-date=14 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120814051327/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/12/ed-sheeran-olympics-closi_n_1771077.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[Taylor Swift]] contacted Sheeran after hearing his music while touring Australia in March 2012.<ref name="billboard.com">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1496478/ed-sheeran-to-record-new-album-on-taylor-swift-tour |title=Ed Sheeran to Record New Album on Taylor Swift Tour |magazine=Billboard |date=16 January 2013 |access-date=8 June 2013 |archive-date=30 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530180835/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1496478/ed-sheeran-to-record-new-album-on-taylor-swift-tour |url-status=live }}</ref> He later co-wrote and provided vocals for "[[Everything Has Changed]]", a single featured on Swift's fourth studio album, ''[[Red (Taylor Swift album)|Red]]''. Sheeran also contributed two songs to One Direction's second studio album, ''[[Take Me Home (One Direction album)|Take Me Home]]'', released in November 2012; the single "[[Little Things (One Direction song)|Little Things]]" became the group's second number-one in the UK.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dan |last=Lane |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/one-direction-score-number-1-single-and-album-1719/ |title=One Direction score Number 1 single AND album! |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |date=18 November 2012 |access-date=19 November 2012 |location=United Kingdom |archive-date=30 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830142315/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/one-direction-score-number-1-single-and-album-__2564/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Sheeran's album peaked at No. 5 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], while "The A Team" reached No. 16 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name="billboard.com"/> In late 2012 and early 2013, he headlined a US tour of 6,000–9,000-capacity venues.<ref name="billboard.com"/> "The A Team" received a nomination for Song of the Year at the [[55th Annual Grammy Awards|2013 Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/grammy-awards/370372-grammy-awards-2013-nominations-frank-ocean-fun|title=2013 Grammy Nominations|date=6 December 2012|publisher=MTV|access-date=6 December 2012|archive-date=20 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120084047/http://www.mtv.co.uk/grammy-awards/news/frank-ocean-fun-lead-2013-grammy-award-nominations|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Elton John]], who runs Sheeran's management company, canvassed the award organisers to get Sheeran a performance slot at the ceremony but was told that Sheeran alone was not high-profile enough. John decided to appear with Sheeran to circumvent this problem.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cMM5zMsq2a8 |title=Ed Sheeran on the Grammys |via=YouTube |date=7 February 2013 |access-date=8 June 2013 |archive-date=10 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210063050/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cMM5zMsq2a8 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sheeran was also featured on some tracks from Irish singer [[Foy Vance]]'s fourth album ''[[Joy of Nothing]]''.<ref>{{cite web | author=folkradiouk | title=Foy Vance new album: Joy of Nothing (+ documentary) | website=Folk Radio UK – Folk Music Magazine | date=10 June 2013 | url=http://www.folkradio.co.uk/2013/06/foy-vance-debut-album-joy-of-nothing-documentary/ | access-date=6 September 2018 | archive-date=15 June 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615024450/http://www.folkradio.co.uk/2013/06/foy-vance-debut-album-joy-of-nothing-documentary/ | url-status=live }}</ref>

From March to September 2013, Sheeran played at arenas and stadiums across North America as the opening act for Swift's [[The Red Tour]].<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=27 October 2012|title=Taylor Swift Tour to Paint the Road 'Red'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474440/taylor-swift-tour-to-paint-the-road-red|magazine=Billboard|access-date=6 December 2012|archive-date=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212163215/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474440/taylor-swift-tour-to-paint-the-road-red|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Telegraph-McLean">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/10859780/Ed-Sheeran-interview-I-dont-make-music-for-critics.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/10859780/Ed-Sheeran-interview-I-dont-make-music-for-critics.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Ed Sheeran interview: 'I don't make music for critics'|last=McLean|first=Craig|date=16 July 2014|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=14 November 2015}}{{cbignore}}</ref> According to Sheeran, it was then his biggest tour, and he added a scarlet RED tattoo to commemorate it.<ref name="MTV-Kaufman">{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=31 October 2012|title=Ed Sheeran Calls Taylor Swift Opening Gig 'Mind-blowing' – Music, Celebrity, Artist News|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1696524/taylor-swift-ed-sheeran-opening-act-red-tour.jhtml|publisher=MTV News|access-date=8 June 2013|archive-date=19 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130419010412/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1696524/taylor-swift-ed-sheeran-opening-act-red-tour.jhtml|url-status=dead}}</ref> In October 2013, Sheeran headlined three sold-out shows at New York's [[Madison Square Garden]].<ref name="Telegraph-McLean"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Garibaldi|first=Christina|date=2 November 2013|title=Taylor Swift Gives Ed Sheeran Some 'Love' With Surprise Concert Appearance|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1716719/ed-sheeran-taylor-swift-concert-surprise-new-york-city/|publisher=MTV News|access-date=14 November 2015|archive-date=9 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209074324/http://www.mtv.com/news/1716719/ed-sheeran-taylor-swift-concert-surprise-new-york-city/|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/videos/watch-ed-sheeran-perform-sweet-thinking-out-loud-for-austin-city-limits-20150403|title=Watch Ed Sheeran Perform Sweet 'Thinking Out Loud' for 'Austin City Limits'|last=Spanos|first=Brittany|author-link=Brittany Spanos|date=3 April 2015|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=14 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151127054936/https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/videos/watch-ed-sheeran-perform-sweet-thinking-out-loud-for-austin-city-limits-20150403|archive-date=27 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the concert, Sheeran debuted new songs, including "[[Tenerife Sea]]",<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=20 March 2014|title=If Ed Sheeran Sees His Own Shadow, Will He Drop A New Single in April?|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1724462/if-ed-sheeran-sees-his-own-shadow-will-he-drop-a-new-single-in-april/|publisher=MTV News|access-date=14 November 2015|archive-date=17 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117192133/http://www.mtv.com/news/1724462/if-ed-sheeran-sees-his-own-shadow-will-he-drop-a-new-single-in-april/|url-status=dead}}</ref> a future track on his second studio album. Sheeran released "[[I See Fire]]" on 5 November 2013. The song is featured in the [[closing credits|end credits]] of the film ''[[The Hobbit: The Desolation of Smaug]]'', [[Music of The Hobbit series|the film's soundtrack]], and on the deluxe version of his second album.<ref>{{cite news|last=Harris|first=Jamie|date=5 November 2013|title=Ed Sheeran debuts new solo song 'I See Fire' for 'Hobbit' movie|url=http://www.digitalspy.com.au/music/news/a528784/ed-sheeran-debuts-new-solo-song-i-see-fire-for-hobbit-movie-listen.html|work=Digital Spy|location=Australia|access-date=19 February 2014|archive-date=24 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224025856/http://www.digitalspy.com.au/music/news/a528784/ed-sheeran-debuts-new-solo-song-i-see-fire-for-hobbit-movie-listen.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Sheeran was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]] at the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards|2014 Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5819883/grammy-awards-2014-full-nominations-list-complete-nominees |title=Grammy Awards 2014: Full Nominations List |magazine=Billboard |date=6 December 2013 |access-date=29 March 2014 |archive-date=13 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813121343/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5819883/grammy-awards-2014-full-nominations-list-complete-nominees |url-status=live }}</ref>

===2014–2015: ''×'' ("''Multiply''")===

On 24 March 2014, Sheeran performed at the [[Teenage Cancer Trust]] charity concert at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London where he unveiled "Take It Back", a track that would appear on the deluxe version of the second album.<ref>{{cite news|last=Talbot|first=Martin|date=25 March 2014|title=British singer/songwriters get Teenage Cancer Trust benefit shows off to a storming start at London's Royal Albert Hall|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-and-passenger-unveil-new-songs-at-teenage-cancer-trust-show__3893/|publisher=Official Charts Company|access-date=14 November 2015|archive-date=17 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117103613/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-and-passenger-unveil-new-songs-at-teenage-cancer-trust-show__3893/|url-status=live}}</ref> "[[Sing (Ed Sheeran song)|Sing]]", the lead single, was released on 7 April 2014. Sonically, the song is a departure from Sheeran's previous recordings.<ref name="BB-Lipshutz">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6041312/ed-sheeran-billboard-cover-story|title=Ed Sheeran Un-Zipped: On His Pharrell-Produced Single, Being a Sex Symbol and Turning Betrayal Into Song (Cover Story)|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|date=7 April 2014|magazine=Billboard|access-date=14 November 2015|archive-date=20 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120073226/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6041312/ed-sheeran-billboard-cover-story|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/52180/ed-sheeran-sing-pharrell/|title=Ed Sheeran Teams Up With Pharrell for New Single "Sing": Listen|last=St. Asaph|first=Katherine|date=7 April 2014|magazine=Time|access-date=14 November 2015|archive-date=6 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200806015632/https://time.com/52180/ed-sheeran-sing-pharrell/|url-status=live}}</ref> "Sing" was intended to create hype over the album release, but from concern that this might alienate Sheeran's fan base, "[[One (Ed Sheeran song)|One]]", an acoustic ballad, was released on 16 May 2014;<ref name="Telegraph-McLean"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/music/2014/08/23/interview-ed-sheeran-x-pharrell-elton-john/14403209/|title=Interview: Ed Sheeran on 'X,' Pharrell and Elton John|last=Masley|first=Ed|date=27 August 2014|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|access-date=14 November 2015|archive-date=16 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220816094521/https://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/music/2014/08/23/interview-ed-sheeran-x-pharrell-elton-john/14403209/|url-status=live}}</ref> "One" also marked the first of several promotional singles released leading to the album release. By early June 2014, "Sing" had earned Sheeran his first number-one single in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lane|first=Dan|date=8 June 2014|title=Ed Sheeran scores first ever Number 1 single with Sing|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-scores-first-ever-number-1-single-with-sing__4192/|publisher=Official Charts Company|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=16 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220816094524/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-scores-first-ever-number-1-single-with-sing__4192/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Sheeran's second studio album, ''[[x (Ed Sheeran album)|×]]'' ("Multiply"), was released worldwide on 23 June 2014. Spanning three years, Sheeran wrote more than 120 songs for the album.<ref name="RS-Doyle">{{cite news|last=Doyle|first=Patrick|date=7 April 2014|title=Ed Sheeran's Heartache and Wildest Nights: Behind His Raw LP 'X'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/ed-sheerans-heartache-and-wildest-nights-behind-his-raw-lp-x-20140407|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=14 November 2015|archive-date=4 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904063115/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/ed-sheerans-heartache-and-wildest-nights-behind-his-raw-lp-x-20140407|url-status=live}}</ref> The album features tracks produced by [[Rick Rubin]], [[Pharrell Williams]] and [[Benny Blanco]],<ref name="RS-Doyle"/> as well as that of Gosling's.<ref name="BB-Lipshutz"/> ''×'' peaked at number one in both the UK Albums Chart and the US ''Billboard'' 200. To support the album, Sheeran embarked on [[x Tour (Ed Sheeran tour)|a world tour]] starting on 6 August 2014 at [[Osaka]], Japan. On 27 September 2014, Sheeran was one of the headline acts at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]] prior to the [[2014 AFL Grand Final]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Cashmere|first=Paul|date=28 September 2014|title=Baron Ed Sheeran Performs With Sir Tom Jones at AFL Grand Final|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/baron-ed-sheeran-performs-with-sir-tom-jones-at-afl-grand-final-20140928|publisher=Noise11|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=17 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117015417/http://www.noise11.com/news/baron-ed-sheeran-performs-with-sir-tom-jones-at-afl-grand-final-20140928|url-status=live}}</ref>
Following "[[Don't (Ed Sheeran song)|Don't]]", "[[Thinking Out Loud]]" was released on 24 September 2014 as the album's third single. Unlike his previous music videos, Sheeran took the lead role in the single's accompaniment, where he performed a ballroom dance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Parker|first=Lyndsey|date=9 October 2014|title=Sheeran Busts Out the Ballroom Moves in 'Thinking Out Loud' Video|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sheeran-busts-out-the-ballroom-moves-in-thinking-out-loud-video-20141009|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=14 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151114180621/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sheeran-busts-out-the-ballroom-moves-in-thinking-out-loud-video-20141009|url-status=live}}</ref> It became his second single to reach number one in the UK,<ref>{{cite news|last=Moss|first=Liv|date=2 November 2014|title=Ed Sheeran's Thinking Out Loud claims longest climb to Number 1 ever!|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-s-thinking-out-loud-claims-longest-climb-to-number-1-ever-__6890/|publisher=Official Charts Company|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=1 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151101201824/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-s-thinking-out-loud-claims-longest-climb-to-number-1-ever-__6890/|url-status=live}}</ref> and it also spent eight weeks at number two on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] (with only "[[Uptown Funk]]" by [[Mark Ronson]] featuring [[Bruno Mars]] keeping it from top spot).<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6495240/mark-ronson-bruno-mars-10th-week-hot-100|title="Uptown Funk" spends 10th week at No. 1, while Ed Sheeran spends eighth week at No. 2|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=11 March 2015|magazine=Billboard|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=6 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106142614/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6495240/mark-ronson-bruno-mars-10th-week-hot-100|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2014, combined [[streaming media|streams]] on Sheeran's catalogue in [[Spotify]] reached 860 million; Spotify named him the most-streamed artist and ''×'' the most-streamed album.<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=3 December 2014|title=Ed Sheeran is Spotify's Most-Streamed Act for 2014|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6334841/ed-sheeran-is-spotifys-most-streamed-act-for-2014|magazine=Billboard|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=4 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104025649/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6334841/ed-sheeran-is-spotifys-most-streamed-act-for-2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In the same year, the album made Sheeran [[iTunes]]' best-selling artist in the UK, Ireland and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=8 December 2014|title=Ed Sheeran tops iTunes' UK bestseller list|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/dec/08/ed-sheeran-itunes-uk-bestsellers-list-sam-smith-frozen-coldplay-paolo-nutini|work=The Guardian|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=11 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151011225904/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/dec/08/ed-sheeran-itunes-uk-bestsellers-list-sam-smith-frozen-coldplay-paolo-nutini|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rutledge|first=Daniel|date=9 December 2014|title=Pharrell, Ed Sheeran and Frozen top NZ iTunes 2014 charts|url=http://www.3news.co.nz/entertainment/pharrell-ed-sheehan-and-frozen-top-nz-itunes-2014-charts-2014120906|work=[[3 News]]|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://archive.today/20141209135850/http://www.3news.co.nz/entertainment/pharrell-ed-sheehan-and-frozen-top-nz-itunes-2014-charts-2014120906|archive-date=9 December 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>

[[File:Ed Sheeran at Wembley 3 (19050650853).jpg|thumb|upright|Sheeran on stage at [[Wembley Stadium]], July 2015]]

''×'' was nominated for Album of the Year at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards|57th Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-grammys-2015-nominees-winners-list-story.html|title=Grammys 2015: Complete list of winners and nominees|work=Los Angeles Times|date=8 February 2015|access-date=25 November 2015|archive-date=13 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151113092219/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-grammys-2015-nominees-winners-list-story.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Sheeran performed "Thinking Out Loud" alongside [[John Mayer]], [[Questlove]] and [[Herbie Hancock]] at the ceremony.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Flanagan|first=Andrew|title=Grammys 2015: Ed Sheeran Performs 'Thinking Out Loud' with Questlove, Herbie Hancock, John Mayer|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/grammys-2015/grammy-performances/6465571/grammys-2015-ed-sheeran-thinking-out-loud-herbie-hancock-john-mayer-questlove|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=7 August 2015|date=8 February 2015|archive-date=29 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150729075854/http://www.billboard.com/articles/grammys-2015/grammy-performances/6465571/grammys-2015-ed-sheeran-thinking-out-loud-herbie-hancock-john-mayer-questlove|url-status=live}}</ref> On 25 February, Sheeran won [[Brit Award for British Male Solo Artist|British Male Solo Artist]] and British Album of the Year for ''×'' at the [[2015 Brit Awards]].<ref name="Brits 2015">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/feb/25/brit-awards-2015-the-full-list-of-winners|title=Brit awards 2015: the full list of winners|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=25 February 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 November 2015|archive-date=21 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121213835/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/feb/25/brit-awards-2015-the-full-list-of-winners|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 May he received the [[Ivor Novello Award]] for Songwriter of the Year.<ref name="Novello">{{cite news|last=Denham|first=Jess|date=21 May 2015|title=Ivor Novello Awards 2015 winners list: Ed Sheeran, Clean Bandit and Hozier triumph|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/ivor-novello-awards-2015-winners-list-ed-sheeran-clean-bandit-and-hozier-triumph-10267714.html|work=The Independent|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=29 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929231816/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/ivor-novello-awards-2015-winners-list-ed-sheeran-clean-bandit-and-hozier-triumph-10267714.html|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 June, Sheeran co-hosted the [[2015 Much Music Video Awards]] in Toronto, where he performed the singles, "Thinking Out Loud" and "[[Photograph (Ed Sheeran song)|Photograph]]"; he also won two awards, Best International Artist and Most Buzzworthy International Artist or Group.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/entertainment/ed-sheeran-the-weeknd-rule-the-mmvas-drake-drops-in-as-a-surprise-1.2432898|title=Ed Sheeran, the Weeknd rule the MMVAs; Drake drops in as a surprise|last=Patch|first=Nick|date=21 June 2015|publisher=[[CTV News]]|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=17 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117063740/http://www.ctvnews.ca/entertainment/ed-sheeran-the-weeknd-rule-the-mmvas-drake-drops-in-as-a-surprise-1.2432898|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://mmva.muchmusic.com/check-out-the-full-list-of-mmva-winners-now/?theme=mobile |title=Check Out The Full List of MMVA Winners Now! |work=MMVA |access-date=27 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208110312/http://mmva.muchmusic.com/check-out-the-full-list-of-mmva-winners-now/?theme=mobile |archive-date=8 December 2015 }}</ref> On 27 June, Sheeran performed as the opening act for [[The Rolling Stones]] in their [[Zip Code Tour]] date in Kansas City's [[Arrowhead Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=28 June 2015|title=See Rolling Stones Perform 'Beast of Burden' With Ed Sheeran|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-rolling-stones-perform-beast-of-burden-with-ed-sheeran-20150628|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=22 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122051756/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-rolling-stones-perform-beast-of-burden-with-ed-sheeran-20150628|url-status=live}}</ref> On 10–12 July 2015, Sheeran performed sold-out shows at London's [[Wembley Stadium]]. The shows, which were announced in November 2014, were part of his world tour.<ref>{{cite news |date=17 November 2014 |title=Ed Sheeran to play biggest solo show to date at Wembley |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/30079487 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=29 November 2014 |archive-date=6 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150306105732/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/30079487 |url-status=live }}</ref> The concert was documented and aired on 16 August 2015 on [[NBC]]; the one-hour special ''Ed Sheeran – Live at Wembley Stadium'' also included behind-the-scenes footage.<ref>{{cite news |last=Spanos |first=Brittany |date=24 July 2015 |title=Ed Sheeran Announces 'Live at Wembley Stadium' TV Special |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/ed-sheeran-announces-live-at-wembley-stadium-tv-special-20150724 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=12 December 2017 |archive-date=10 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010005048/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/ed-sheeran-announces-live-at-wembley-stadium-tv-special-20150724 |url-status=live }}</ref> In November 2015 Sheeran released the DVD ''[[Jumpers for Goalposts: Live at Wembley Stadium]]''; the title is a nod to playing concerts at Wembley Stadium, the home of [[English football]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Watch the trailer for Ed Sheeran's exuberant concert film 'Jumpers for Goalposts' |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2015/09/17/ed-sheeran-concert-film-jumpers-for-goalposts-trailer/77544832/ |date=17 September 2015 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |access-date=28 March 2018 |archive-date=28 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328232532/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2015/09/17/ed-sheeran-concert-film-jumpers-for-goalposts-trailer/77544832/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2015, Sheeran wrote "[[Love Yourself]]" for [[Justin Bieber]]'s fourth album.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran Wrote Song for Justin Bieber's New Album, but Not One Direction's |url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2015/10/1/ed-sheeran-wrote-song-for-justin-biebers-new-album-but-not-o.html |work=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |date=1 October 2015 |access-date=22 March 2017 |archive-date=11 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211113709/http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2015/10/1/ed-sheeran-wrote-song-for-justin-biebers-new-album-but-not-o.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Sheeran had initially planned to put the song on his third album ÷ and added that the track would have been scrapped before Bieber took the song.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Ed Sheeran Reveals 'Love Yourself' Was Originally Written For His New Album 'Divide' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7647997/ed-sheeran-love-yourself-justin-bieber-divide-interview |access-date=22 March 2017 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=9 January 2017 |archive-date=15 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315032836/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7647997/ed-sheeran-love-yourself-justin-bieber-divide-interview |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2015, he sang along with [[Macklemore]] on the track "Growing Up".<ref>{{cite news | last=Denham | first=Jess | title=Macklemore and Ed Sheeran just dropped a surprise new song | website=The Independent | date=5 August 2015 | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/macklemore-and-ed-sheeran-drop-surprise-song-growing-up-about-becoming-a-dad-10441024.html | access-date=6 September 2018 | archive-date=6 September 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906130012/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/macklemore-and-ed-sheeran-drop-surprise-song-growing-up-about-becoming-a-dad-10441024.html | url-status=live }}</ref> On 26 September, Sheeran performed at the 2015 [[Global Citizen Festival]] in [[Central Park]]'s Great Lawn in New York, an event organised by [[Coldplay]] lead singer, [[Chris Martin]], that advocates an end to extreme global poverty. Sheeran headlined the festival along with [[Beyoncé]], Coldplay and [[Pearl Jam]]. The festival was broadcast on NBC in the US on 27 September and the [[BBC]] in the UK on 28 September.<ref name="Festival">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/6620421/beyonce-coldplay-pearl-jam-new-york-2015-global-citizen-festival |title=Beyoncé, Coldplay, Pearl Jam to Headline New York's 2015 Global Citizen Festival |last=Hampp |first=Andrew |date=9 July 2015 |magazine=Billboard |access-date=5 August 2015 |archive-date=31 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150731005100/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/6620421/beyonce-coldplay-pearl-jam-new-york-2015-global-citizen-festival |url-status=live }}</ref> Sheeran co-hosted the [[2015 MTV Europe Music Awards]] on 25 October in [[Milan]], Italy. He won the awards for Best Live Act and Best Live Stage;<ref>{{cite news|last=Vincent|first=Alice|date=26 October 2015|title=MTV EMAs 2015: Five things we learned|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/news/mtv-emas-2015-justin-bieber-ed-sheeran/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/news/mtv-emas-2015-justin-bieber-ed-sheeran/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|work=The Telegraph|access-date=15 November 2015}}{{cbignore}}</ref> the latter was in recognition for his performance at the 2014 [[V Festival]] in England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-festivals/10675886/Justin-Timberlake-and-the-Killers-to-headline-V-Festival-2014.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-festivals/10675886/Justin-Timberlake-and-the-Killers-to-headline-V-Festival-2014.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Justin Timberlake and the Killers to headline V Festival 2014|last=Waters|first=Lowenna|date=4 March 2014|work=The Telegraph|access-date=15 November 2015}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Sheeran won the Breakthrough award at the 2015 [[Billboard Touring Awards|''Billboard'' Touring Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Angermiller|first=Michele Amabile|date=20 November 2015|title=One Direction, Ed Sheeran, & The Grateful Dead Big Winners at Billboard Touring Awards|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6770115/billboard-touring-conference-winners-one-direction-ed-sheeran|magazine=Billboard|access-date=21 November 2015|archive-date=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410212433/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6770115/billboard-touring-conference-winners-one-direction-ed-sheeran|url-status=live}}</ref> His single from ''×'', "Thinking Out Loud", earned him two [[Grammy Award]]s at the [[58th Annual Grammy Awards|2016 ceremony]]: [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]].<ref name="Grammys 2016">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/live/2016/feb/15/grammy-awards-2016-live-adele-taylor-swift-kendrick-lamar|title=Grammy Awards 2016: performances and winners – as it happened|date=15 January 2016|work=Guardian|access-date=28 August 2019|archive-date=24 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724092441/https://www.theguardian.com/music/live/2016/feb/15/grammy-awards-2016-live-adele-taylor-swift-kendrick-lamar|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2016, ''×'' was named the second-best-selling album worldwide in 2015, behind ''[[25 (Adele album)|25]]'' by [[Adele]].<ref>{{cite news|title=One in six albums sold worldwide is by a UK star|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-36332019|publisher=BBC|date=20 May 2016|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=12 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220812185044/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-36332019|url-status=live}}</ref>

===2016–2018: ''÷'' ("''Divide''") ===

On 13 December 2016, after a year long hiatus and social media break, Sheeran tweeted a picture and changed his Twitter, Facebook and Instagram to a light blue, implying the release of a new album—each of Sheeran's previous albums were a single-coloured background with a solid mathematical symbol.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ed Sheeran teases new music with return to social media|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-teases-new-music-return-social-media-1911605|work=NME|date=13 December 2016|access-date=13 December 2016|archive-date=13 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161213185131/http://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-teases-new-music-return-social-media-1911605|url-status=live}}</ref> On 2 January, he posted a 10-second video on Twitter and other social media platforms, revealing the tracklist and cover art of his fourth studio album, ''[[÷ (album)|÷]]'' ("Divide"), which was released on 3 March 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2017/01/ed-sheeran-tracklist-cover-art-release-date-divide-album|title=Ed Sheeran Shares Tracklist, Cover Art, and Release Date for New Album '÷'|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|access-date=12 January 2017|archive-date=16 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116180920/http://www.complex.com/music/2017/01/ed-sheeran-tracklist-cover-art-release-date-divide-album|url-status=live}}</ref> The album debuted at number one in the UK, the US, Germany, Australia, Canada and other major markets.<ref name="Fastest selling UK">{{cite news|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-smashes-official-chart-records-as-is-the-fastest-selling-album-by-a-male-artist-ever__18447/|title=Ed Sheeran smashes Official Chart records as ÷ is the fastest-selling album by a male artist ever|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=10 March 2017|access-date=10 March 2017|archive-date=28 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428075832/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-smashes-official-chart-records-as-is-the-fastest-selling-album-by-a-male-artist-ever__18447/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Biggest selling US">{{cite news|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|title=Ed Sheeran's 'Divide' Bows at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart With 2017's Biggest Debut|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7718243/ed-sheerans-divide-bows-at-no-1-on-billboard-200-chart-with|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=12 March 2017|access-date=13 March 2017|archive-date=13 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313023817/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7718243/ed-sheerans-divide-bows-at-no-1-on-billboard-200-chart-with|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Australian Charts: Ed Sheeran 'Divide' Debuts At No 1|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/australian-charts-ed-sheeran-divide-debuts-at-no-1-20170312|publisher=Noise 11|date=12 March 2017|access-date=12 March 2017|archive-date=12 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312125950/http://www.noise11.com/news/australian-charts-ed-sheeran-divide-debuts-at-no-1-20170312|url-status=live}}</ref> With first week sales of 672,000 it is the fastest-selling album by a male solo artist in the UK, and [[Lists of fastest-selling albums|third fastest in UK chart history]] behind ''[[25 (Adele album)|25]]'' by [[Adele]] and ''[[Be Here Now (album)|Be Here Now]]'' by [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]].<ref name="Fastest selling UK"/> It had the biggest first-week sales of 2017 in the US, until it was surpassed by Taylor Swift's ''[[Reputation (Taylor Swift album)|Reputation]]''.<ref name="Biggest selling US"/>

On 6 January, Sheeran released two singles, "[[Shape of You]]" and "[[Castle on the Hill]]"; the theme of the latter single Sheeran's upbringing in his home town of [[Framlingham]] in Suffolk, with the [[castle]] referring to [[Framlingham Castle]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ed Sheeran Returns With Two New Tracks 'Castle on the Hill' and "Shape of You"|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2017/01/ed-sheeran-castle-on-hill-shape-of-you-divide|website=Complex|access-date=6 January 2017|archive-date=7 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170107170909/http://www.complex.com/music/2017/01/ed-sheeran-castle-on-hill-shape-of-you-divide|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the release of these singles, Sheeran co-hosted the [[BBC Radio 1 Breakfast Show]] with Scott Mills where it was implied that he would possibly make an appearance at the [[Glastonbury Festival]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=BBC Radio 1|title=Ed Sheeran's Back! 10 minutes 47 seconds of his best bits!|website=[[YouTube]]|date=6 January 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_1xHMQGDo78|access-date=6 January 2017|archive-date=6 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106235303/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_1xHMQGDo78&gl=US&hl=en|url-status=live}}</ref> It was also during this show that Sheeran used a new [[Martin Guitars|Martin guitar]] that featured the ÷ logo (of his new album) on both the headstock and body of the acoustic guitar.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ed Sheeran – Castle on the Hill (Live)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ytb7J0ciBcE|via=YouTube|publisher=BBC Radio 1|access-date=11 January 2017|date=6 January 2017|archive-date=12 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112074747/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ytb7J0ciBcE|url-status=live}}</ref> Both singles went on to break the [[Spotify]] day one streaming record, with a combined total of over 13 million streams in 24 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/ed-sheeran-broken-spotifys-day-154304017.html|title=Ed Sheeran has broken Spotify's 'day one' streaming record|date=9 January 2017|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|access-date=11 January 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110022334/https://uk.news.yahoo.com/ed-sheeran-broken-spotifys-day-154304017.html|archive-date=10 January 2017}}</ref>

On 13 January, "Shape of You" and "Castle on the Hill" entered the [[UK Singles Chart]] at number one and number two, the first time in history an artist has taken the top two UK chart positions with new songs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ed Sheeran takes top two chart positions|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-38609564|publisher=BBC|date=13 January 2017|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=15 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220815234929/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-38609564|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day he also became the first artist to debut at number one and number two on the [[GfK Entertainment Charts|German Single Charts]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gfk-entertainment.com/news/historischer-rekord-ed-sheeran-startet-als-erster-kuenstler-auf-1-und-2-der-single-charts.html | access-date=17 January 2017 | quote=(translated from German) | title=Historical record: Ed Sheeran starts as the first artist on 1 and 2 of the Official German single charts | archive-date=18 January 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118051453/http://www.gfk-entertainment.com/news/historischer-rekord-ed-sheeran-startet-als-erster-kuenstler-auf-1-und-2-der-single-charts.html | url-status=live }}</ref> On 15 January, the songs debuted at number one and number two on the [[ARIA Singles Chart]], the first time this has been achieved in the history of the Australian chart.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ed Sheeran Creates Chart History Down Under|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7655311/ed-sheeran-chart-history-down-under|magazine=Billboard|date=16 January 2017|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=20 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210820091928/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7655311/ed-sheeran-chart-history-down-under|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 January, "Shape of You" debuted at number one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], while "Castle on the Hill" entered at number six; this made Sheeran the first artist ever to have two songs simultaneously debut in the US top 10.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ed Sheeran Debuts Atop Hot 100 With 'Shape of You' & in Top 10 With 'Castle on the Hill'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7655347/hot-100-ed-sheeran-shape-of-you-debuts-number-one|magazine=Billboard|date=17 January 2017|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=22 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201022112917/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7655347/hot-100-ed-sheeran-shape-of-you-debuts-number-one|url-status=live}}</ref> The team behind [[TLC (group)|TLC]]'s song "[[No Scrubs]]" were given writing credits on "Shape of You" after fans and critics found similarities between elements of the two songs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7735550/ed-sheeran-tlc-no-scrubs-writers-shape-of-you-credits|magazine=Billboard|title=Ed Sheeran Adds TLC's 'No Scrubs' Songwriters to 'Shape of You' Credits|date=21 March 2017|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=1 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180601162619/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7735550/ed-sheeran-tlc-no-scrubs-writers-shape-of-you-credits|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Ed Sheehan - Divide Tour.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Sheeran performing in Miami during his Divide Tour, August 2017. It became the most attended, and [[List of highest-grossing concert tours|highest-grossing tour of all time]] in August 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran breaks U2's tour record |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-49203859 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=2 August 2019 |archive-date=2 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802154415/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-49203859 |url-status=live }}</ref>]]
On 26 January, Sheeran announced dates for the beginning of the Divide Tour with shows in Europe, South America and North America from 17 March until 14 June 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/ed-sheeran-new-album-release-date-1942763|title=Ed Sheeran new album '÷' – release date, tour dates, new songs & more|date=26 January 2017|work=[[NME]]|access-date=26 January 2017|archive-date=25 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125155636/http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/ed-sheeran-new-album-release-date-1942763|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 February, Sheeran released "[[How Would You Feel (Paean)]]". Though not an official single, the song peaked at number two in the UK.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Connor |first=Roisin |title=Ed Sheeran has three songs in the top five |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/ed-sheeran-how-would-you-feel-single-no-1-shape-of-you-rag-n-bone-man-human-uk-charts-a7590996.html |date=21 February 2017 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |location=London |access-date=22 February 2017 |archive-date=22 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222172734/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/ed-sheeran-how-would-you-feel-single-no-1-shape-of-you-rag-n-bone-man-human-uk-charts-a7590996.html |url-status=live }}</ref> By 11 March 2017, Sheeran had accumulated ten top-10 singles from ''÷'' on the UK Singles Chart, breaking Scottish DJ [[Calvin Harris]]'s record of nine top-10 singles from one album.<ref name="Album record">{{cite news|title=Calvin Harris has some mixed feelings about Ed Sheeran beating his UK chart record|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/uk-album-chart/news/a823229/calvin-harris-ed-sheeran-chart-record-mixed-feelings/|work=Digital Spy|date=22 October 2017|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=8 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108105411/http://www.digitalspy.com/music/uk-album-chart/news/a823229/calvin-harris-ed-sheeran-chart-record-mixed-feelings/|url-status=live}}</ref> On 25 June, Sheeran headlined the final night of [[Glastonbury Festival|Glastonbury]], performing in front of 135,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glastonburyfestivals.co.uk/ed-sheeran-confirmed-as-sunday-night-headliner/|title=Ed Sheeran Confirmed as Sunday Night Headliner|website=Glastonbury Festival|date=16 March 2017 |access-date=16 March 2017|archive-date=17 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317143357/http://www.glastonburyfestivals.co.uk/ed-sheeran-confirmed-as-sunday-night-headliner/|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[2017 MTV Video Music Awards]] Sheeran was named Artist of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtvpress.com/press-releases/2017/08/28/2017-vma-winners-and-performances|author=MTV Press|date=27 August 2017|access-date=26 May 2018|title=2017 "VMA" Winners and Performances|archive-date=28 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828144030/http://www.mtvpress.com/press-releases/2017/08/28/2017-vma-winners-and-performances|url-status=live}}</ref> The fourth single from ''÷'', "[[Perfect (Ed Sheeran song)|Perfect]]", reached number one in the UK and Australia, and a stripped-down acoustic version of the song titled "Perfect Duet", a collaboration with [[Beyoncé]], reached number one in the US and the UK,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8063597/ed-sheeran-beyonce-perfect-billboard-hot-100-number-one|title=Ed Sheeran & Beyonce's 'Perfect' Tops Billboard Hot 100|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=11 December 2017|magazine=Billboard|access-date=11 December 2017|archive-date=12 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212043503/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8063597/ed-sheeran-beyonce-perfect-billboard-hot-100-number-one|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheerans-perfect-remix-features-beyonce__21134/|title=Ed Sheeran's Perfect remix features Beyonce|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|last=White|first=Jack|date=30 November 2017|access-date=30 November 2017|archive-date=1 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201113413/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheerans-perfect-remix-features-beyonce__21134/|url-status=live}}</ref> becoming the year's [[List of UK Singles Chart Christmas number ones|UK Christmas number one]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Beaumont-Thomas|first=Ben|title=Ed Sheeran scores first Christmas No 1 with Perfect|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/22/ed-sheeran-first-christmas-no-1-perfect-beyonce-andrea-bocelli|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=22 December 2017|date=22 December 2017|archive-date=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222191657/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/22/ed-sheeran-first-christmas-no-1-perfect-beyonce-andrea-bocelli|url-status=live}}</ref> On 7 November, Taylor Swift revealed that Sheeran collaborated on the song "[[End Game (Taylor Swift song)|End Game]]" for her sixth studio album ''[[Reputation (Taylor Swift album)|Reputation]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Taylor Swift Reputation Track List|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8030087/taylor-swift-reputation-tracklist-ed-sheeran-future-end-game|magazine=Billboard|date=7 November 2017|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=8 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108112827/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8030087/taylor-swift-reputation-tracklist-ed-sheeran-future-end-game|url-status=live}}</ref> The song, which also features rapper [[Future (rapper)|Future]], was released on 10 November.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Renner Brown|first=Eric|title=Taylor Swift unites with Ed Sheeran and Future on 'End Game'|url=https://ew.com/music/2017/11/10/taylor-swift-ed-sheeran-future-end-game/|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=14 November 2017|archive-date=13 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113211437/http://ew.com/music/2017/11/10/taylor-swift-ed-sheeran-future-end-game/|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 4 December, Sheeran was named Spotify's most-streamed artist of 2017 with 6.3&nbsp;billion streams. He has Spotify's biggest album of the year with ''÷'' streamed 3.1&nbsp;billion times, and the top song with "Shape of You" with 1.4&nbsp;billion streams.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Ed Sheeran Tops Spotify's 2017 Most-Streamed List |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8055138/ed-sheeran-tops-spotify-2017-most-streamed-list |magazine=Billboard |date=5 December 2017 |access-date=5 December 2017 |archive-date=26 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426093533/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8055138/ed-sheeran-tops-spotify-2017-most-streamed-list |url-status=live }}</ref> On 5 December 2017, hip-hop artist [[Eminem]] announced that Sheeran had collaborated on the song "[[River (Eminem song)|River]]" for his ninth studio album ''[[Revival (Eminem album)|Revival]]''.<ref name="Eminem album">{{cite news |title=Eminem's new album 'Revival' features Ed Sheeran on one song |url=http://entertainment.ie/music/news/Eminems-new-album-Revival-features-Ed-Sheeran-on-one-song-yes-really/399935.htm |work=Entertainment.ie. |date=6 December 2017 |access-date=27 August 2022 |archive-date=3 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903200119/http://entertainment.ie/music/news/Eminems-new-album-Revival-features-Ed-Sheeran-on-one-song-yes-really/399935.htm |url-status=live }}</ref> On working with Eminem, Sheeran stated, "He is one of the reasons I started writing songs, and was such a pleasure to work with him."<ref name="Eminem album"/> In December 2017, Sheeran appeared on [[BBC Radio 1]]'s [[Live Lounge]], performing his song "Perfect" and a duet of [[The Pogues]]' festive classic "[[Fairytale of New York]]" with [[Anne-Marie (singer)|Anne-Marie]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran and Anne-Marie Cover 'Fairytale Of New York' |url=https://www.mtv.co.uk/news/1xgnt2/ed-sheeran-and-annemarie-cover-fairytale-of-new-york |work=MTV |access-date=20 December 2018 |archive-date=21 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221044412/http://www.mtv.co.uk/ed-sheeran/news/ed-sheeran-and-annemarie-cover-fairytale-of-new-york |url-status=live }}</ref> [[File:Ed Sheeran and Don McLean as they perform backstage.jpg|thumb|right|Sheeran backstage in Los Angeles with [[Don McLean]] in August 2018]]

On 3 January 2018, "Shape of You" was named the [[List of UK top-ten singles in 2017|best-selling single of 2017]] in the UK,<ref>{{cite news|title=The Top 40 biggest songs of 2017 on the Official Chart|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-top-40-biggest-songs-of-2017-on-the-official-chart__21327/|work=Official Charts Company|date=11 January 2018|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=3 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103074642/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-top-40-biggest-songs-of-2017-on-the-official-chart__21327/|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[List of Billboard Hot 100 number ones of 2017|best-selling single of 2017 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in the US.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2017/hot-100-songs|title=Hot 100 Songs – Year-End 2017|year=2017|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|access-date=3 January 2018|archive-date=16 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216064214/https://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2017/hot-100-songs|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, ''÷'' was named the best-selling album of 2017 in the UK,<ref>{{cite news|title=Top 40 biggest albums of 2017 on the Official Chart|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-top-40-biggest-albums-of-2017-on-the-official-chart__21316/|work=Official Charts Company|issue=3 January 2018|date=10 January 2018|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=3 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103133518/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-top-40-biggest-albums-of-2017-on-the-official-chart__21316/|url-status=live}}</ref> and the US.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Ed Sheeran's 'Divide' Is Nielsen Music's Top Album of 2017 in U.S. |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8085932/ed-sheeran-divide-nielsen-music-top-album-2017 |magazine=Billboard |issue=3 January 2018 |date=10 January 2018 |access-date=27 August 2022 |archive-date=8 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211108050224/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8085932/ed-sheeran-divide-nielsen-music-top-album-2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> As the best-selling artist worldwide for 2017, the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI) named him the [[Global Recording Artist of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran officially named the best-selling global recording artist of 2017 |url=http://www.ifpi.org/news/Ed-Sheeran-officially-named-the-best-selling-global-recording-artist-of-2017 |website=[[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI) |date=26 February 2018 |access-date=12 March 2020 |archive-date=25 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025113053/https://www.ifpi.org/news/Ed-Sheeran-officially-named-the-best-selling-global-recording-artist-of-2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the [[2018 Brit Awards]] held at [[The O2 Arena|the O<sub>2</sub> Arena]] in London on 21 February, Sheeran performed "[[Supermarket Flowers]]", and received the Global Success Award from Elton John and Rolling Stones guitarist [[Ronnie Wood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brits.co.uk/winners|title=Winners|website=BRIT Awards|access-date=23 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222224456/http://www.brits.co.uk/winners|archive-date=22 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Sheeran played to over 950,000 people in Australia and New Zealand in March and April, making it the biggest concert tour in Australasian music history, overtaking the previous record set by [[Dire Straits]] in 1986.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran adds final Australian shows; breaking all records |url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/ed-sheeran-adds-final-australian-shows-breaking-all-records/news-story/ac81a728476a08c7d59e1c2a1fd79ef7 |work=News.com.au |issue=26 May 2017 |date=15 December 2017 |access-date=27 August 2022 |archive-date=12 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211212013235/https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/ed-sheeran-adds-final-australian-shows-breaking-all-records/news-story/ac81a728476a08c7d59e1c2a1fd79ef7 |url-status=live }}</ref> In April, the IFPI named ''÷'' the [[List of best-selling albums#Best-selling album by year worldwide|best-selling album worldwide]] of 2017.<ref>{{citation|contribution=Global Top 10 Albums of 2017|page=9|title=IFPI Global Music Report 2018|publisher=International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|access-date=24 April 2018|url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/GMR2018.pdf|mode=cs1|archive-date=24 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424202534/http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/GMR2018.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[2018 Billboard Music Awards|2018 ''Billboard'' Music Awards]] on 20 May, Sheeran performed "[[Galway Girl (Ed Sheeran song)|Galway Girl]]" from [[Phoenix Park]] in [[Dublin]], Ireland, and picked up six awards, including [[Billboard Music Award for Top Artist|Top Artist]] and [[Billboard Music Award for Top Hot 100 Artist|Top Hot 100 Artist]].<ref name="Billboard 2018">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/8456842/billboard-music-awards-2018-winners-list-bbmas |title=Here Are All the Winners From the 2018 Billboard Music Awards |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=20 May 2018 |access-date=21 May 2018 |archive-date=24 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524084717/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/8456842/billboard-music-awards-2018-winners-list-bbmas |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018 Sheeran wrote songs for boy bands. "[[Trust Fund Baby]]", by [[Why Don't We]], was released on 1 February 2018,<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Rising Pop Group Why Don't We Drops New Song 'Trust Fund Baby,' Written by Ed Sheeran |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8097673/why-dont-we-new-song-trust-fund-baby-ed-sheeran |access-date=13 February 2020 |magazine=Billboard |date=26 February 2018 |archive-date=16 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116013334/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8097673/why-dont-we-new-song-trust-fund-baby-ed-sheeran |url-status=live }}</ref> and "Summer On You", by [[PrettyMuch]], was released on 21 June 2018.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=PRETTYMUCH Drops Sunny Ed Sheeran-Penned Single 'Summer on You': Listen |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8462126/prettymuch-summer-on-you |magazine=Billboard |date=26 February 2018 |access-date=13 February 2020 |archive-date=27 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827042121/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8462126/prettymuch-summer-on-you |url-status=live }}</ref>

===2019–2022: ''No.6 Collaborations Project'' and ''='' ("''Equals''")===
[[File:Promotion message from Ed Sheeran in 2019.webm|thumb|Sheeran speaking at a promotional event in New Zealand in 2019]]
On 10 May 2019, Sheeran released the single "[[I Don't Care (Ed Sheeran and Justin Bieber song)|I Don't Care]]", a duet with [[Justin Bieber]], from his fourth studio album ''[[No.6 Collaborations Project]]''. On [[Spotify]], "I Don't Care" debuted with 10.977 million daily global streams, breaking the platform's [[List of most-streamed songs on Spotify#Most-streamed songs in a single day|single-day streaming record]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/news%26id%3D316107%26title%3DSPOTIFY-U.S.-TOP-25%3A-ED-%26-BIEBER-HEAT-UP%26redirect%3Dmobile|title=HITS Daily Double : Rumor Mill – Spotify U.S. Top 25: Ed & Bieber Heat Up|website=HITS Daily Double|access-date=15 May 2019|archive-date=5 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605180553/http://hitsdailydouble.com/news%26id%3D316107%26title%3DSPOTIFY-U.S.-TOP-25:-ED-%26-BIEBER-HEAT-UP%26redirect%3Dmobile|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2019/05/11/ed-sheeran-justin-biebers-i-dont-care-breaks-single-day-spotify-streaming-record/|title=Ed Sheeran & Justin Bieber's "I Don't Care" Breaks Single-Day Spotify Streaming Record|website=Headline Planet|date=11 May 2019|access-date=15 May 2019|archive-date=13 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513090139/https://headlineplanet.com/home/2019/05/11/ed-sheeran-justin-biebers-i-dont-care-breaks-single-day-spotify-streaming-record/|url-status=live}}</ref> The song debuted at number one in the UK, Australia and other markets, and number two in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=20 May 2019|access-date=18 May 2019|archive-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321235817/https://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8512166/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-number-one-seventh-week-hot-100|title=Lil Nas X's 'Old Town Road' Tops Billboard Hot 100 for Seventh Week, Ed Sheeran & Justin Bieber's 'I Don't Care' Debuts at No. 2|magazine=Billboard|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-date=9 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609040703/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8512166/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-number-one-seventh-week-hot-100|url-status=live}}</ref> On 31 May, "[[Cross Me]]" featuring [[Chance the Rapper]] and [[PnB Rock]], debuted at number 9 in the UK.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran and Justin Bieber's I Don't Care clings on to the UK's Official Singles Chart Number 1 for a third week |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-and-justin-biebers-i-dont-care-clings-on-to-the-uks-official-singles-chart-number-1-for-a-third-week__26458/ |access-date=31 May 2019 |work=Official Charts Company |archive-date=31 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531181818/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-and-justin-biebers-i-dont-care-clings-on-to-the-uks-official-singles-chart-number-1-for-a-third-week__26458/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Released on 28 June 2019, "[[Beautiful People (Ed Sheeran song)|Beautiful People]]" featuring [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]] debuted at number 3 in the UK and number 4 in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=8 July 2019|access-date=6 July 2019|archive-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321235817/https://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 July, Sheeran released two new songs, "[[Best Part of Me]]" featuring [[Yebba]], and "[[Blow (Ed Sheeran, Chris Stapleton and Bruno Mars song)|Blow]]" with [[Bruno Mars]] and [[Chris Stapleton]]. On 12 July, he released the album, along with "[[Antisocial (Ed Sheeran and Travis Scott song)|Antisocial]]" with [[Travis Scott]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/ed-sheeran-and-travis-scott-share-video-for-new-song-antisocial-watch/|title=Ed Sheeran and Travis Scott Share Video for New Song "Antisocial": Watch|website=Pitchfork|date=12 July 2019|access-date=12 July 2019|archive-date=23 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201023003235/https://pitchfork.com/news/ed-sheeran-and-travis-scott-share-video-for-new-song-antisocial-watch/|url-status=live}}</ref> The album debuted at number one in the UK, the US, Australia and other markets.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8523132/ed-sheeran-no-6-is-no-1-star-studded-collaborations-project-debuts-no-1-billboard-albums-chart|title=Ed Sheeran's 'No. 6 Collaborations Project' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|magazine=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=21 July 2019|access-date=22 July 2019|archive-date=2 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102062554/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8523132/ed-sheeran-no-6-is-no-1-star-studded-collaborations-project-debuts-no-1-billboard-albums-chart|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/albums-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Albums|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=20 July 2019|access-date=22 July 2019|archive-date=22 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022111652/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/albums-chart|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 August, Sheeran wrapped up the 260-show Divide Tour with the last of four homecoming gigs in [[Ipswich]], Suffolk;<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran's Ipswich show 'might be the last loop pedal gig' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-49454009 |date=27 August 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=27 August 2019 |archive-date=27 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827184328/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-49454009 |url-status=live }}</ref> the tour included, for example, his performance for over 100,000 people at [[Malmi Airport]] in [[Helsinki]], Finland on 24 July.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/police_fine_two_drone_operators_at_ed_sheeran_concert/10893023 |title=Police fine two drone operators at Ed Sheeran concert |work=[[Yle News]] |date=25 July 2019 |access-date=27 October 2021 |archive-date=27 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211027105603/https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/police_fine_two_drone_operators_at_ed_sheeran_concert/10893023 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 30 August, the seventh single from the album, "[[Take Me Back to London]]" featuring [[Stormzy]], reached number one in the UK.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran and Stormzy's Take Me Back To London lands second week at Number 1 |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-and-stormzys-take-me-back-to-london-lands-second-week-at-number-1__27215/ |access-date=7 September 2019 |work=Official Charts Company |archive-date=6 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906203145/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-and-stormzys-take-me-back-to-london-lands-second-week-at-number-1__27215/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2019, Sheeran co-wrote country music singer [[Kenny Chesney]]'s single "[[Tip of My Tongue (Kenny Chesney song)|Tip of My Tongue]]".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nashcountrydaily.com/2019/07/12/kenny-chesney-releases-savory-new-single-tip-of-my-tongue-listen/ | title=Kenny Chesney to Release New Single, "Tip of My Tongue" | work=Nash Country Daily | date=12 July 2019 | access-date=16 October 2019 | first=Jim | last=Casey | archive-date=16 October 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016210402/http://www.nashcountrydaily.com/2019/07/12/kenny-chesney-releases-savory-new-single-tip-of-my-tongue-listen/ | url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2019, Sheeran was named artist of the decade by the [[Official Charts Company]] for being the most successful performer in the UK album and singles charts of the 2010s.<ref name="Decade"/> Eight of his songs featured in the Official Chart Company's chart of the decade with three songs inside the top 5—"[[Shape of You]]" was named number one.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-uks-official-top-100-biggest-songs-of-the-decade-2010-2019__27936/ |title=The UK's Official Top 100 biggest songs of the decade 2010 – 2019 |website=Official Charts Company |access-date=11 December 2019 |archive-date=11 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211082710/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-uks-official-top-100-biggest-songs-of-the-decade-2010-2019__27936/ |url-status=live }}</ref> His four albums spent a combined 41 weeks at number one in the UK, the [[List of UK Albums Chart number ones of the 2010s#Artists with the most weeks at number one|most weeks at number one in the 2010s]], and five weeks more than Adele in second.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/chart/albums|title=The Official UK Top 40 Albums Chart|publisher=[[BBC Radio 1]]|access-date=6 August 2019|archive-date=8 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110508213226/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/chart/albums|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/albums-chart/|title=The Official UK Top 40 Albums Chart|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=6 August 2019|archive-date=29 November 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20151129140104/http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/albums-chart/|url-status=live}}</ref> He had the third and fourth [[List of best-selling albums of the 2010s in the United Kingdom|best-selling album of the 2010s]] in the UK, with only Adele's two albums selling more.<ref name="Decade"/> Globally, [[Spotify]] named him the second [[List of most-streamed artists on Spotify#By decade|most streamed artist]] of the decade behind [[Drake (musician)|Drake]].<ref name="Decade"/> On 21 December 2020, after being on hiatus after having his first child with Cherry Seaborn in August, he released the surprise single, "[[Afterglow (Ed Sheeran song)|Afterglow]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-make-return-christmas-present-tomorrow-the-afterglow-2842855 |title=Ed Sheeran returns with new single 'Afterglow' |last=Daly |first=Rhian |website=[[NME (magazine)|NME]] |date=21 December 2020 |access-date=31 December 2020 |archive-date=8 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220408154100/https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-make-return-christmas-present-tomorrow-the-afterglow-2842855 |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[File:Coldplay and Ed Sheeran (2021).jpg|thumb|left|Sheeran (right) on stage with [[Coldplay]] at the [[Shepherd's Bush Empire|O<sub>2</sub> Shepherd's Bush Empire]], west London in October 2021]]
On 25 June 2021, Sheeran released "[[Bad Habits (Ed Sheeran song)|Bad Habits]]", the lead single from his upcoming fifth studio album.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9585940/ed-sheeran-bad-habits-single|title=Ed Sheeran Announces 'Bad Habits' Single: 'Feels Great to Be Back!'|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=11 June 2021|access-date=11 June 2021|archive-date=6 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210706205710/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9585940/ed-sheeran-bad-habits-single/|url-status=live}}</ref> His 10th UK number one single, the song spent eleven consecutive weeks at the top of the [[UK Singles Chart]] and [[Irish Singles Chart]], topped the charts in Australia, Canada and Germany among others, and peaked at number two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in the US.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran scores 10th UK Number 1 single with Bad Habits: "This is an amazing thing" |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-scores-10th-uk-number-1-single-with-bad-habits-this-is-an-amazing-thing__33511/ |access-date=27 September 2021 |work=Official Charts Company |date=2 July 2021 |archive-date=11 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210711212523/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-scores-10th-uk-number-1-single-with-bad-habits-this-is-an-amazing-thing__33511/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran's 'Bad Habits' Tops Global Charts |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9606390/ed-sheeran-bad-habits-no-1-global-charts/ |access-date=27 September 2021 |magazine=Billboard |date=26 July 2021 |archive-date=25 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210925065501/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9606390/ed-sheeran-bad-habits-no-1-global-charts/ |url-status=live }}</ref> His eleventh week at number one in the UK saw him become the first British solo artist to notch up 52 weeks at Number 1 across his catalogue, with only Elvis Presley (80 weeks) and The Beatles (69 weeks) achieving more weeks at the summit.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran claims record-breaking 52 weeks – a full year – at Number 1 on Official Singles Chart |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-claims-record-breaking-52-weeks-a-full-year-at-number-1-on-official-singles-chart__34033/ |access-date=27 September 2021 |work=Official Charts Company |date=15 September 2021 |archive-date=27 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210927095334/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-claims-record-breaking-52-weeks-a-full-year-at-number-1-on-official-singles-chart__34033/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 19 August, Sheeran announced that his fifth studio album, ''[[= (album)|=]]'' ("Equals"), would be released on 29 October 2021. The cover was painted by him during the first [[COVID-19 lockdowns|COVID-19 lockdown]], and is based on the changes his life had during the last four years, including marriage, having a child and losing friends. The promotional single "[[Visiting Hours (song)|Visiting Hours]]" was released alongside the announcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/ed-sheeran-announces-equals-album-visiting-hours|title=Ed Sheeran Announces Album and Shares New Song "Visiting Hours"|last=Price|first=Joe|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=19 August 2021|access-date=19 August 2021|archive-date=19 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210819141350/https://www.complex.com/music/ed-sheeran-announces-equals-album-visiting-hours|url-status=live}}</ref> On 9 September, he was part of the 2021 Kickoff Experience ahead of the American NFL season opening game.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9611621/ed-sheeran-performance-nfl-2021-kickoff-experience-tampa/|title=Ed Sheeran to Perform at NFL 2021 Kickoff Experience in Tampa|first=Gil|last=Kaufman|magazine=Billboard|date=6 August 2021|access-date=6 August 2021|archive-date=6 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210806175335/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9611621/ed-sheeran-performance-nfl-2021-kickoff-experience-tampa/|url-status=live}}</ref> Released on 10 September, "[[Shivers (Ed Sheeran song)|Shivers]]" dethroned "Bad Habits" at the top of the UK and Irish singles charts.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran replaces himself at Number 1 on the Official Singles Chart with Shivers |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-replaces-himself-at-number-1-on-the-official-singles-chart-with-shivers__34060/ |access-date=27 September 2021 |work=Official Charts Company |date=17 September 2021 |archive-date=27 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210927100957/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-replaces-himself-at-number-1-on-the-official-singles-chart-with-shivers__34060/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Topping the charts in most major markets, ''='' became his fifth UK number-one album, and fourth US number one.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran scores fifth Number 1 on Official Albums Chart with Equals: "Thank you for listening" |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-scores-fifth-number-1-on-official-albums-chart-with-equals-thank-you-for-listening-__34388/ |access-date=11 November 2021 |work=Official Charts Company |archive-date=6 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211106000729/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-scores-fifth-number-1-on-official-albums-chart-with-equals-thank-you-for-listening-__34388/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9656431/ed-sheeran-fourth-number-one-album-equals-billboard-200/|title=Ed Sheeran Scores Fourth No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 With '='|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|magazine=Billboard|date=7 November 2021|access-date=7 November 2021|archive-date=16 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211116121625/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9656431/ed-sheeran-fourth-number-one-album-equals-billboard-200/|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Platinum Jubilee 2022 - Platinum Pageant (52124436078) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Sheeran playing in front of [[Buckingham Palace]] during the Queen's [[Platinum Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Platinum Jubilee]] in June 2022]] 
On 29 November 2021, Sheeran and [[Elton John]] released "[[Merry Christmas (song)|Merry Christmas]]", a duet single for charity. Inspired by a scene from the 2003 romantic-comedy film ''[[Love Actually]]'', the song's music video sees the duo pay homage to scenes from past British Christmas hits, including "[[Last Christmas]]", "[[Walking in the Air]]", "[[Merry Christmas Everyone]]", and "[[Stay Another Day]]".<ref>{{cite news |title=Elton John, Ed Sheeran Pay Tribute to Holiday Hits in 'Merry Christmas' Video |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/elton-john-ed-sheeran-merry-christmas-1266233/ |access-date=3 December 2021 |magazine=Rolling Stone |archive-date=3 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211203205354/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/elton-john-ed-sheeran-merry-christmas-1266233/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Love Actually"/> All of the UK profits from the song went to the Ed Sheeran Suffolk Music Foundation and the Elton John AIDS Foundation.<ref name="Love Actually">{{cite magazine|last=Bowenbank|first=Starr|title=Ed Sheeran & Elton John Reveal 'Merry Christmas' Duet Release Date With 'Love Actually' Spoof|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/elton-john-ed-sheeran-merry-christmas-duet-release-date-charity-1235003496/|date=29 November 2021|access-date=29 November 2021|magazine=Billboard|archive-date=30 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211130210647/https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/elton-john-ed-sheeran-merry-christmas-duet-release-date-charity-1235003496/|url-status=live}}</ref> Debuting at number one in the UK Singles Chart on 10 December, it was Sheeran's 12th hit single.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran & Elton John's Merry Christmas debuts at Number 1 on the Official Singles Chart |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-elton-johns-merry-christmas-debuts-at-number-1-on-the-official-singles-chart__34653/ |access-date=11 December 2021 |work=Official Charts Company |archive-date=10 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211210193825/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ed-sheeran-elton-johns-merry-christmas-debuts-at-number-1-on-the-official-singles-chart__34653/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 23 December, Sheeran featured on the remix of [[Fireboy DML]]'s song "[[Peru (song)|Peru]]".<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Ed Sheeran Hops on Remix of Fireboy DML's Hit Single 'Peru'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/ed-sheeran-fireboy-dml-peru-remix-1276009/|access-date=25 December 2021|magazine=Rolling Stone|archive-date=16 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220816094523/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/ed-sheeran-fireboy-dml-peru-remix-1276009/|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 11 February 2022, Sheeran released a duet version of "[[The Joker and the Queen]]" featuring [[Taylor Swift]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/ed-sheeran-confirms-the-joker-and-the-queen-remix-taylor-swift-1235029027/|title=Ed Sheeran Confirms 'The Joker and the Queen' Remix With 'Good Friend' Taylor Swift|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|magazine=Billboard|date=9 February 2022|access-date=9 February 2022|archive-date=16 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220816094522/https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/ed-sheeran-confirms-the-joker-and-the-queen-remix-taylor-swift-1235029027/|url-status=live}}</ref> On 4 March, he featured in "[[Bam Bam (Camila Cabello song)|Bam Bam]]", collaborating for the second time with [[Camila Cabello]]. Later that month he collaborated with Colombian singer [[J Balvin]] in the singles "[[Sigue]]" and "[[Forever My Love]]". Sheeran commenced his +–=÷x Tour (Mathematics Tour) on 21 March.<ref>{{cite web|date=17 September 2021|title=Ed Sheeran Announces The Mathematics Tour Of UK, Europe For 2022|url=https://www.thisisdig.com/ed-sheeran-mathematics-tour-2022/|access-date=14 August 2022|website=Dig!|archive-date=23 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220623201606/https://www.thisisdig.com/ed-sheeran-mathematics-tour-2022/|url-status=live}}</ref> He played warm-up shows at the [[Electric Ballroom]] in Camden Town, London before the main tour began with two concerts at [[Croke Park]] in Dublin.<ref>{{cite web|date=22 September 2021|title=Surprise! Ed Sheeran to open his 2022 tour in Dublin, not Cork|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/culture/entertainment/ed-sheeran-dublin|access-date=15 August 2022|website=IrishCentral.com|archive-date=18 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220818073012/https://www.irishcentral.com/culture/entertainment/ed-sheeran-dublin|url-status=live}}</ref> On 22 April, Sheeran released the fifth single from ''='', "[[2step (song)|2step]]" featuring [[Lil Baby]], before releasing a version of the song featuring Ukrainian pop-rock band [[Antytila]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-teams-up-with-ukrainian-band-antytila-for-reworked-2step-3216770?utm_source%3Drss%26utm_medium%3Drss%26utm_campaign%3Ded-sheeran-teams-up-with-ukrainian-band-antytila-for-reworked-2step|title=Ed Sheeran teams up with Ukrainian band Antytila for reworked '2Step'|website=[[NME]]|date=2 May 2022|access-date=2 May 2022|archive-date=2 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220502161712/https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-teams-up-with-ukrainian-band-antytila-for-reworked-2step-3216770?utm_source%3Drss%26utm_medium%3Drss%26utm_campaign%3Ded-sheeran-teams-up-with-ukrainian-band-antytila-for-reworked-2step|url-status=live}}</ref> 2022 also saw Sheeran venture into heavier styles of music, releasing a new version of "Bad Habits" with the [[pop metal]] group [[Bring Me the Horizon]] in February.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Daw |first=Stephen |date=8 February 2022 |title=Ed Sheeran & Bring Me the Horizon Open Up the 2022 Brit Awards With Rollicking 'Bad Habits' |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/awards/ed-sheeran-bring-me-the-horizon-bad-habits-2022-brit-awards-1235028729/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=9 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220209163933/https://www.billboard.com/music/awards/ed-sheeran-bring-me-the-horizon-bad-habits-2022-brit-awards-1235028729/ |archive-date=9 February 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> Later that year it was reported that he was in contact with Suffolk [[extreme metal]] group [[Cradle of Filth]] over a possible project, with frontman [[Dani Filth]] confirming progress on the collaboration in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/a-cradle-of-filthed-sheeran-collaboration-is-actually-really-happening|title=A Cradle Of Filth/Ed Sheeran collaboration is actually, really happening|work=Metal Hammer|first=Liz|last=Scarlett|date=31 August 2022|access-date=17 September 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220920170528/https://www.loudersound.com/news/a-cradle-of-filthed-sheeran-collaboration-is-actually-really-happening|archive-date=20 September 2022|url-status=live}}</ref> In July, he launched a collaboration with clothing brand [[Lucy & Yak]] which was inspired by the artwork of =.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lester |first=Daisy |date=14 July 2022 |title=Ed Sheeran launches sustainable clothing collection with Lucy & Yak |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/extras/indybest/fashion-beauty/womens-clothing/ed-sheeran-lucy-yak-clothing-collection-b2123009.html |access-date=12 October 2023 |website=[[The Independent]] |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220715065619/https://www.independent.co.uk/extras/indybest/fashion-beauty/womens-clothing/ed-sheeran-lucy-yak-clothing-collection-b2123009.html |archive-date=15 July 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 29 September, Sheeran released the single "[[Celestial (Ed Sheeran song)|Celestial]]", a collaboration with Japanese media franchise [[Pokémon]]. On November, "Shivers" became Sheeran's 11th song to reach 1 billion streams on [[Spotify]]. He celebrated via an [[Instagram]] post, saying that he was currently filming a music video for his next album, scheduled to be released the following year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ed Sheeran on Instagram: "Shivers has hit a billion streams on Spotify ! My 11th as an artist and 15th as a writer, thank you so so much for streaming it. See you next year for a new album x" |url=https://www.instagram.com/reel/CkdGjonI08u/ |access-date=4 November 2022 |website=Instagram |archive-date=4 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221104003200/https://www.instagram.com/reel/CkdGjonI08u/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Sheeran was spotted at a beach in the coastal Suffolk town of [[Lowestoft]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Boggis |first=Mark |date=3 November 2022 |title=Teen all smiles after capturing selfie with superstar Ed Sheeran |url=https://www.lowestoftjournal.co.uk/news/ed-sheeran-lowestoft-new-music-video-filming-9354312 |access-date=4 November 2022 |website=Lowestoft Journal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221103060416/https://www.lowestoftjournal.co.uk/news/ed-sheeran-lowestoft-new-music-video-filming-9354312 |archive-date=3 November 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=3 November 2022 |title=Ed Sheeran: Singer films music video on Lowestoft beach |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-63438430 |access-date=4 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221104194805/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-63438430 |archive-date=4 November 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref>

===2023–present: ''-'' ("''Subtract''") and ''Autumn Variations'' ===
On 1 March 2023, Sheeran officially announced on all social media platforms that his sixth studio album, ''[[- (album)|-]]'' ("Subtract"), would be released on 5 May 2023.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sheeran |first=Ed |title= Ed Sheeran - I had been working on Subtract for a decade, trying... {{!}} Facebook |date=1 March 2023 |url= https://www.facebook.com/EdSheeranMusic/posts/743281280497779/ |access-date=1 March 2023 |website=Facebook |archive-date=1 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230301091947/https://www.facebook.com/EdSheeranMusic/posts/pfbid0btSmHkTqANcE37hTkvu5gRjE8TDZt4uuXNTDgguYavtqzkVuRusGh8FZKgpakJd2l |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Beaumont-Thomas|first=Ben|title=New Ed Sheeran album, Subtract, informed by 'fear, depression and anxiety' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/mar/01/new-ed-sheeran-album-subtract-informed-by-fear-depression-and-anxiety|work=The Guardian|date=1 March 2023|access-date=1 March 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230302065048/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/mar/01/new-ed-sheeran-album-subtract-informed-by-fear-depression-and-anxiety|archive-date=2 March 2023|url-status=live}}</ref> Sheeran released the album's lead single, "[[Eyes Closed (Ed Sheeran song)|Eyes Closed]]" with its accompanying music video on 24 March 2023.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Mier |first=Tomás |date=24 March 2023 |title=Ed Sheeran's Sadness Manifests as a Giant Blue Monster in Video for 'Eyes Closed' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/ed-sheeran-eyes-closed-music-video-1234702677/ |access-date=27 March 2023 |magazine=Rolling Stone |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230327185221/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/ed-sheeran-eyes-closed-music-video-1234702677/ |archive-date=27 March 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> "[[Boat (song)|Boat]]" was released as the second single off the record on 21 April 2023.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/ed-sheeran-boat-stream-it-now-1235311931/|title=Ed Sheeran Captures Life's Dark Moments With New Single 'Boat': Stream It Now|last=Aniftos|first=Rania|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=21 April 2023|access-date=26 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230422144110/https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/ed-sheeran-boat-stream-it-now-1235311931/|archive-date=22 April 2023|url-status=live}}</ref> The third single, "[[Life Goes On (Ed Sheeran song)|Life Goes On]]", was released on 5 May 2023.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-transition-country-music-3442579|title=Ed Sheeran eyes "transition into country" music, shares new version of 'Life Goes On' with Luke Combs|last=Singh|first=Surej|magazine=[[NME]]|date=12 May 2023|access-date=12 May 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230523185451/https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-transition-country-music-3442579|archive-date=23 May 2023|url-status=live}}</ref>

In August 2023, Sheeran announced his second album of the year, ''[[Autumn Variations]]'', released on 29 September 2023.<ref>{{cite web |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=24 August 2023 |title=Ed Sheeran Announces Second Album of 2023, 'Autumn Variations,' Reteaming With Aaron Dessner |url=https://variety.com/2023/music/news/ed-sheeran-autumn-variations-album-announce-aaron-dessner-1235703487/ |access-date=24 August 2023 |website=Variety |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230825140732/https://variety.com/2023/music/news/ed-sheeran-autumn-variations-album-announce-aaron-dessner-1235703487/ |archive-date=25 August 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> It is his first studio album for which he owns the copyright, and also his first to be released through [[Gingerbread Man Records]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Autumn Variations [Explicit] by Ed Sheeran on Amazon Music |date=29 September 2023 |access-date=1 September 2023 |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Autumn-Variations-Explicit-Ed-Sheeran/dp/B0CG9NMDPF |via=[[Amazon Music]] |publisher=[[Gingerbread Man Records]] |archive-date=1 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230901072924/https://www.amazon.co.uk/Autumn-Variations-Explicit-Ed-Sheeran/dp/B0CG9NMDPF |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Musical style and influences==
[[File:Eric Clapton 1.jpg|thumb|right|Sheeran appeared on stage with one of his idols [[Eric Clapton]] ''(pictured)'' at the [[Nippon Budokan]] Arena in Tokyo, Japan on 13 April 2016 performing Clapton's "I Will Be There"]]
Sheeran's musical style has been described as [[Pop music|pop]],<ref name=allmusicbio/><ref name="thisisdig">{{cite web|first=Luke|last=Edwards|url=https://www.thisisdig.com/feature/best-ed-sheeran-songs/|title=Best Ed Sheeran Songs: 20 Great Tracks From The Folk-Pop Sensation|website=thisisdig.com|date=1 August 2021|access-date=10 February 2022|archive-date=10 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220210073255/https://www.thisisdig.com/feature/best-ed-sheeran-songs/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Brittany|last=Spanos|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/drakes-more-life-playlist-is-redefining-pop-borders-w472780|title=Drake's 'More Life' Playlist Is Redefining Borders of Blackness in Pop|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=20 March 2017|access-date=10 February 2022|archive-date=14 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614195212/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/drakes-more-life-playlist-is-redefining-pop-borders-w472780|url-status=live}}</ref> [[folk-pop]],<ref name="thisisdig"/><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Maura|last=Johnston|author-link=Maura Johnston |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/review-ed-sheerans-divide-w470271|title=Review: Ed Sheeran's 'Divide'|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=6 March 2017|access-date=10 February 2022|quote=Our take on the folk-pop troubadour's third album|archive-date=7 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107021647/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/review-ed-sheerans-divide-w470271|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://startribune.com/gallery-british-folk-pop-star-ed-sheeran-plays-the-xcel/327796431/|title=British folk pop star Ed Sheeran plays the Xcel|work=Star Tribune|date=15 September 2015|access-date=10 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530185941/http://www.startribune.com/gallery-british-folk-pop-star-ed-sheeran-plays-the-xcel/327796431/|archive-date=30 May 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[soft rock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/channel/Music/News/watch-ed-sheeran-is-making-a-comeback-with-some-new-tunes-20170102|title=Watch: Ed Sheeran is making a comeback with some new tunes|website=[[News24 (website)|News24]]|date=2 January 2017|access-date=10 February 2022|archive-date=3 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211003032613/https://www.news24.com/channel/music/news/watch-ed-sheeran-is-making-a-comeback-with-some-new-tunes-20170102|url-status=live}}</ref> Sheeran also incorporates [[Rapping|rap]] into his music.<ref name="thisisdig"/> Sheeran's earliest memories include listening to the records of [[Joni Mitchell]], [[Bob Dylan]] and [[Elton John]]'s ''[[Greatest Hits (Elton John album)|Greatest Hits]]''.<ref name="Telegraph 2017"/> According to Sheeran, the album that introduced him to music was [[Van Morrison]]'s ''[[Irish Heartbeat]]''.{{sfn|Nolan|2012|pp=1–6}} During his childhood his father took him to live concerts that would inspire his musical creations. These included seeing [[Eric Clapton]] at the [[Royal Albert Hall]], [[Paul McCartney]] in [[Birmingham]], and Bob Dylan.<ref>{{cite book |title=''Ed Sheeran: A Visual Journey'' |date=2014 |publisher=Running Press |isbn=9780762456963 |location=[S.l.] |page=27}}</ref> On the influence of Clapton, Sheeran states, "He's the reason I started playing guitar".<ref name="Clapton">{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran Opens Up About His A-List Pals, from His Clapton Collab to Taking Shots with Beyoncé |url=http://people.com/music/ed-sheeran-famous-friends-eric-clapton-collaboration-beyonce-taylor-swift/ |website=People.com |date=6 December 2017 |access-date=27 August 2022 |archive-date=23 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623193935/https://people.com/music/ed-sheeran-famous-friends-eric-clapton-collaboration-beyonce-taylor-swift/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He singled out Clapton's performance at the [[Party at the Palace]] in the [[Buckingham Palace Garden|grounds of Buckingham Palace]], "I was eleven when I saw Eric Clapton play at the [[Golden Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II|Queen's Golden Jubilee]] concert in June 2002. I remember him walking on stage with this rainbow-coloured [[Stratocaster]] and playing the first riff of '[[Layla]]'. I was hooked. Two days later I bought a black Stratocaster copy for £30 that came with an [[Amplifier|amp]]. All I did for the next month was try to play that 'Layla' riff."<ref>{{cite book |last=Butah |first=Philip |title=''Ed Sheeran: A Visual Journey'' |date=2014 |publisher=Hachette UK}}</ref>

{{blockquote|In a complicated world, Sheeran's musical ''[[modus operandi]]'' is straightforward; to create well-crafted, expertly vague songs that unite people. His songs are vessels broad enough to soundtrack both a first dance and a funeral procession, a gut-punch break-up and a trawl around a harshly lit shopping centre. They're for life's big moments, with all the cinematic edge of a [[Richard Curtis]] film. He's also malleable – when he's done with [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]], for example, he doesn't need an image overhaul to then revert to balladry. If one genre isn't to your tastes, then fear not, another will be along soon.|Michael Cragg in ''[[The Guardian]]'' on Sheeran's style of music and mass appeal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Music for general societal exhaustion: why Ed Sheeran can't lose |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2022/jun/22/music-ed-sheeran-musician-2021 |access-date=23 October 2022 |work=The Guardian |first=Michael |last=Cragg |date=22 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023180252/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2022/jun/22/music-ed-sheeran-musician-2021 |archive-date=23 October 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref>}}

Sheeran has also cited [[the Beatles]], [[Nizlopi]] and [[Eminem]] as his biggest musical influences.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/urban/253058-ed-sheeran-the-interview |title=Ed Sheeran – The Interview |website=[[MTV]] |access-date=29 November 2014 |archive-date=17 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717183636/http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/urban/253058-ed-sheeran-the-interview |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.axs.com/news/interview-with-uk-pop-sensation-ed-sheeran-14282 |title=Interview with UK Pop Sensation Ed Sheeran |website=axs.com |date=20 January 2012 |access-date=29 November 2014 |archive-date=17 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717212809/https://www.axs.com/news/interview-with-uk-pop-sensation-ed-sheeran-14282 |url-status=live }}</ref> He is also a fan of heavier music and cites bands such as [[Cradle of Filth]], [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], [[Korn]], [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]] and [[Bring Me the Horizon]] as other influences.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-says-he-would-not-be-opposed-to-creating-a-death-metal-album-2992978 |title=Dani Filth responds to Ed Sheeran saying he "would not be opposed to creating" a death metal album |website=[[NME]] |last=Robinson |first=Ellie |date=14 July 2021 |access-date=28 May 2022 |archive-date=28 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220528021003/https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-says-he-would-not-be-opposed-to-creating-a-death-metal-album-2992978 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/ed-sheeran-korn-photo|title=Here's A Photo Of Ed Sheeran Hanging Out With Korn's Head|website=[[Kerrang!]]|date=24 October 2018|access-date=28 May 2022|archive-date=28 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220528021003/https://www.kerrang.com/ed-sheeran-korn-photo|url-status=live}}</ref> As a teenager, he also had a ''[[Kerrang!]]'' subscription.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/bring-me-the-horizon-and-ed-sheeran-are-going-to-write-a-song-together|title=Bring Me The Horizon and Ed Sheeran are going to write a song together|website=[[Kerrang!]]|last=Carter|first=Emily|date=10 February 2022|access-date=28 May 2022|archive-date=28 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220528021004/https://www.kerrang.com/bring-me-the-horizon-and-ed-sheeran-are-going-to-write-a-song-together|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Sheeran, he had a stutter in his speech when he was younger, and he credited rapping along to Eminem's ''[[The Marshall Mathers LP]]'' for helping him stammer less.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/ed-sheeran-on-hard-drinking-nights-taylor-swift-true-love-w470599 |title=Ed Sheeran: Up All Night With Pop's Hardcore Troubadour |first=Patrick |last=Doyle |date=7 March 2017 |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=27 August 2022 |archive-date=5 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405183447/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/ed-sheeran-on-hard-drinking-nights-taylor-swift-true-love-w470599 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also inspired by "[[Cannonball (Damien Rice song)|Cannonball]]" singer-songwriter [[Damien Rice]] in 2002, with Sheeran stating, "seeing him play this small club in Ireland, I was able to meet him, and he was unbelievably cool. I went straight home and started writing songs. I would not be doing what I'm doing now if he'd been a jerk."<ref>{{cite news|title=Ed Sheeran: The Music That Made Me|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/ed-sheeran-the-music-that-made-me-20150508|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=19 December 2017|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222053135/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/ed-sheeran-the-music-that-made-me-20150508|url-status=live}}</ref> He also played the guitar to [[Westlife]]'s ''[[Unbreakable – The Greatest Hits Volume 1|Greatest Hits]]'' album when he was ten, citing them as one of his influences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.news/a-list-fan-ed-sheerans-role-in-the-reforming-of-westlife/1282542/|title=A-list fan Ed Sheeran's role in the reforming of Westlife|publisher=metro.news|date=24 October 2018|access-date=25 October 2018|archive-date=25 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025071341/https://www.metro.news/a-list-fan-ed-sheerans-role-in-the-reforming-of-westlife/1282542/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://evoke.ie/2018/10/23/showbiz/gossip/ed-sheeran-wrote-westlife-songs|title=Ed Sheeran wrote Westlife songs two years BEFORE the band decided to reunite|publisher=evoke.ie|date=23 October 2018|access-date=24 October 2018|archive-date=24 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024113348/https://evoke.ie/2018/10/23/showbiz/gossip/ed-sheeran-wrote-westlife-songs|url-status=live}}</ref> Sheeran collaborated with his idol Eric Clapton in April 2016, with Sheeran stating to ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine, "I sang on Eric Clapton's album ''[[I Still Do]]''. It's one thing having him on mine, but being on his, that's an honour that you can't ever pinpoint on how great that is. I did something for his record, and I was credited as 'Angelo Mysterioso', appearing as a guest on Clapton's 'I Will Be There', in addition to performing the song with Clapton on stage, and he did something for my record performing a guitar solo on '[[Dive (Ed Sheeran song)|Dive]]' on Sheeran's album ''÷'' and was credited as 'Angelo Mysterioso'."<ref name="Clapton"/> Sheeran also cited [[Taylor Swift]] as one of his influences, suggesting in 2015 their respective success drives each other on.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/music/news/a31012/ed-sheeran-says-hes-inspired-by-taylor-swift-and-beyonce/|title=Ed Sheeran Says Taylor Swift's Mega Success Inspires Him|date=21 May 2015|access-date=13 May 2020|archive-date=21 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200521233537/https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/music/news/a31012/ed-sheeran-says-hes-inspired-by-taylor-swift-and-beyonce/|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Other ventures==
===Gingerbread Man Records===
In March 2015, Sheeran announced he was setting up a record label, Gingerbread Man Records, which is a deal with [[Warner Music Group]].<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=23 March 2015|title=Ed Sheeran announces new record label 'Gingerbread'|url=https://www.nme.com/news/ed-sheeran/83813|work=NME|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=17 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117022115/http://www.nme.com/news/ed-sheeran/83813|url-status=live}}</ref> The label was launched in August 2015 alongside its accompanying YouTube channel.<ref>{{cite news|last=Strecker|first=Erin|date=25 August 2015|title=Ed Sheeran Talks About His Label Gingerbread Man Records in New Video|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6677590/ed-sheeran-gingerbread-man-records-label-video|magazine=Billboard|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=31 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031142735/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6677590/ed-sheeran-gingerbread-man-records-label-video|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Jamie Lawson (musician)|Jamie Lawson]], the label's first signee, met Sheeran while they were both in London's folk circuit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/jamie-lawson-a-mystery-despite-big-hit-and-spot-on-ed-sheerans-label-oh-and-hes-not-irish/story-fni0cvc9-1227303922365|title=Jamie Lawson a mystery despite big hit and spot on Ed Sheeran's label – oh, and he's not Irish|last=Moran|first=Jonathon|date=14 April 2015|work=The Telegraph|location=Australia|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150418012738/http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/jamie-lawson-a-mystery-despite-big-hit-and-spot-on-ed-sheerans-label-oh-and-hes-not-irish/story-fni0cvc9-1227303922365|archive-date=18 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Lawson released his [[Jamie Lawson (album)|self-titled debut album]] on 9 October 2015, which has earned him a number one in the UK Albums Chart.<ref>{{cite news|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=23 October 2015|title=Jamie Lawson tops Official Albums Chart: "I'm really over the moon"|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/jamie-lawson-tops-official-albums-chart-i-m-really-over-the-moon-__11118/|publisher=Official Charts Company|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-date=26 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151026001143/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/jamie-lawson-tops-official-albums-chart-i-m-really-over-the-moon-__11118/|url-status=live}}</ref> Sheeran signed his second artist, [[Foy Vance]], in November 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last=Katz|first=Jessie|date=30 November 2015|title=Ed Sheeran Signs Foy Vance As Second Artist to His Gingerbread Man Label|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6777952/ed-sheeran-foy-vance-second-artist-gingerbread-man-label|magazine=Billboard|access-date=5 December 2015|archive-date=2 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151202214317/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6777952/ed-sheeran-foy-vance-second-artist-gingerbread-man-label|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Maisie Peters]] also signed with the label in 2021.<ref>{{cite news|last=Savage|first=Mark|date=15 June 2021|title=Maisie Peters: Meet the singer who's been snapped up by Ed Sheeran|work=BBC News|access-date=15 June 2021|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-57468169|archive-date=15 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210615092127/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-57468169|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Bertie Blossoms===
On 29 September 2019, Sheeran announced he was teaming up with his manager Stuart Camp to open a bar located on Portobello Road in [[Notting Hill]]. The bar is called "Bertie Blossoms", and named after his wife Cherry Seaborn.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lothian-McLean|first=Moya|date=1 October 2019|title=Ed Sheeran opens pub in London|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/ed-sheeran-pub-london-notting-hill-launch-bertie-blossoms-bar-a9128156.html|work=Independent|access-date=13 November 2020|archive-date=20 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201120031756/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/ed-sheeran-pub-london-notting-hill-launch-bertie-blossoms-bar-a9128156.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Charity work===
Sheeran performed a gig in Bristol, which raised £40,000 for a charity that reaches out to [[prostitution|street sex workers]]. "It's good to show insight that these people are real people with real emotions and they deserve the same charity work as anyone else," Sheeran said. "There's a lot more popular charities that get a lot of attention. And with certain subjects like this they're often washed over and people don't necessarily give them the attention they deserve." Tickets were available to those taking part in the charity's Give it up for One25 campaign by giving something up for 125 hours and hitting the £40,000 fundraising mark.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-18163708|title=Ed Sheeran gig in Bristol raises £40,000 for One25|date=22 May 2012|work=BBC News|access-date=6 December 2012|archive-date=30 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130430085345/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-18163708|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Ed Sheeran, V Festival 2014, Chelmsford (14788797777).jpg|thumb|left|Sheeran often wears hoodies or [[tartan]] shirts, and frequently donates his clothes to charity shops in Suffolk.]]
Sheeran frequently gives away his clothes to charity shops around Suffolk, his home county.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ed Sheeran donates clothes to Suffolk charity shops|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-26718523|publisher=BBC|date=25 August 2015|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=8 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220408154233/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-26718523|url-status=live}}</ref> An ambassador for [[East Anglia]]'s Children's Hospice, he has donated clothes to the St Elizabeth Hospice charity shop in his home town Framlingham, including eight bags of clothes to the shop in February 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran's clothes given to three Suffolk charity shops |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-26748425 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=26 March 2014 |access-date=3 January 2019 |archive-date=4 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104034917/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-26748425 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2016, he donated 13 bags of clothes to the shop.<ref name="Clothes">{{cite news|title=Ed Sheeran donates shirt worn in Bridget Jones film to charity|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-37422315|work=[[BBC News]]|date=9 January 2018|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=16 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220816203654/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-37422315|url-status=live}}</ref> The tartan shirt worn by Sheeran when he met Renee Zellweger's character, Bridget, in ''[[Bridget Jones's Baby]]'', was auctioned online to raise further funds for the hospice.<ref name="Clothes"/>

On 15 November 2014, Sheeran joined the charity supergroup [[Band Aid 30]] along with other British and Irish pop acts, recording the latest version of the track "[[Do They Know It's Christmas?]]" at [[Sarm West Studios]] in [[Notting Hill]], London, to raise money for the [[West African Ebola virus epidemic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Band Aid 30: One Direction among celebrity line-up|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=11 November 2014 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/11220735/Band-Aid-30-line-up-revealed.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/11220735/Band-Aid-30-line-up-revealed.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |access-date=6 December 2014}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

In November 2015, Sheeran supported the No Cold Homes campaign by the UK charity, [[Turn2us]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.heatworld.com/2015/10/ed-sheeran-is-selling-his-actual-clothes-for-charity |title=Ed Sheeran is selling his ACTUAL clothes for charity |first=Sophie |last=Bronstein |date=22 October 2015 |magazine=[[Heat (magazine)|Heatworld.com]] |access-date=1 December 2015 |archive-date=8 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208173159/http://www.heatworld.com/2015/10/ed-sheeran-is-selling-his-actual-clothes-for-charity |url-status=live }}</ref> Sheeran was one of nearly thirty celebrities, which included [[Helen Mirren]], [[Jeremy Irons]] and [[Hugh Laurie]], to donate items of winter clothing to the campaign, with the proceeds used to help people in the country struggling to keep their home warm in winter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.turn2us.org.uk/About-Us/Our-campaigns/No-Cold-Homes/Auction/Ed-Sheeran |title=About us: Our campaign. Ed Sheeran |website=Turn2us.org |access-date=1 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208094235/https://www.turn2us.org.uk/About-Us/Our-campaigns/No-Cold-Homes/Auction/Ed-Sheeran |archive-date= 8 December 2015}}</ref>

Sheeran teamed up with the cast of the BBC3 mockumentary sitcom ''[[People Just Do Nothing]]'' to perform a charity single for the BBC's biennial telethon [[Comic Relief]] which aired in March 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran and People Just Do Nothing team up for "epic" Comic Relief charity single |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-03-12/ed-sheeran-and-people-just-do-nothing-team-up-for-epic-comic-relief-charity-single/ |access-date=31 July 2019 |work=[[Radio Times]] |archive-date=31 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731233120/https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-03-12/ed-sheeran-and-people-just-do-nothing-team-up-for-epic-comic-relief-charity-single/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He appeared in a November 2017 episode of ''[[Gogglebox]]'' along with other UK celebrities such as [[Ozzy Osbourne]], former [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] frontman [[Liam Gallagher]], and Labour Party leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as part of Channel 4 and [[Cancer Research UK]]'s [[Stand Up to Cancer UK|''Stand Up to Cancer'']] fundraising campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/gogglebox-jeremy-corbyn-liam-gallagher-ed-sheeran-more-2155280#wO61TUIdQSuPbSKz.99 |title=Watch first preview of Liam Gallagher, Jeremy Corbyn, Ed Sheeran on 'Gogglebox' |work=[[NME]] |date=November 2017 |access-date=10 December 2017 |archive-date=11 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211053659/http://www.nme.com/news/tv/gogglebox-jeremy-corbyn-liam-gallagher-ed-sheeran-more-2155280#wO61TUIdQSuPbSKz.99 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In December 2019, he launched his own music foundation, Ed Sheeran Suffolk Music Foundation (ESSMF). In the statement, Sheeran stated it will help artists aged under 18 with "small but hopefully useful grants".<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran launches foundation to help young Suffolk musicians |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-suffolk-50897377 |access-date=13 November 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |archive-date=13 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201113173021/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-suffolk-50897377 |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2020, Sheeran donated £170,000 to his former school [[Thomas Mills High School]] in Framlingham, Suffolk. The donations, which have been made over a two-year period via the Ed Sheeran Suffolk Music Foundation, helped the school to purchase items such as MacBooks, cameras and a photography darkroom.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran donates £170,000 to provide equipment for his former school |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-donates-170000-to-provide-equipment-for-former-school-2671657 |access-date=13 November 2020 |work=[[NME]] |archive-date=13 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201113173022/https://www.nme.com/news/music/ed-sheeran-donates-170000-to-provide-equipment-for-former-school-2671657 |url-status=live }}</ref> The same month, Sheeran made a donation to [[Ipswich Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ed Sheeran makes 'significant' donation to Ipswich Hospital|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-suffolk-52298499|access-date=13 November 2020|work=BBC|archive-date=1 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201101155051/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-suffolk-52298499|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2020, Sheeran made a "founding gift" to launch Suffolk Community Foundation's "Rebuilding Local Lives Appeal" in response to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] on the celebration day of the county, "Suffolk Day". Sheeran has donated over £1 million to local charities in [[Suffolk]] amid the COVID-19 pandemic, including to a children's hospital ward.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran 'Donates Over £1Million To Local Charities In Suffolk' Amid Coronavirus Pandemic |url=https://www.capitalfm.com/artists/ed-sheeran/ed-sheeran-donates-million-pound-charity/ |access-date=13 November 2020 |work=[[Capital (radio network)|Capitalfm]] |place=London |archive-date=20 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201120072438/https://www.capitalfm.com/artists/ed-sheeran/ed-sheeran-donates-million-pound-charity/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Sheeran's parents organised ''The Ed Sheeran Made in Suffolk Legacy Auction'' on 23 October 2020 which ran until 8 November. The auction had 220 lots, including items donated by other celebrities such as [[David Beckham]], [[Kylie Minogue]] and [[Usain Bolt]]. Sheeran has donated some of his personal items including handwritten lyrics from his song "Perfect", lego bricks he played with as a kid, handmade ''You Need Me'' EP from 2009 and a £3 ticket to his first gig at the British Legion in Framlingham. The auction was made to raise money for Suffolk charities such as GeeWizz and Zest who both support children and young adults in the county, including redeveloping a playground for kids with special educational needs and disabilities in Ipswich. In November Sheeran sold one of his paintings, marking the first and only time his art has been made available for sale, which he titled "Dab 2 2020", to the same auction.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ed Sheeran to sell abstract artwork for charity auction|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/news/ed-sheeran-art-painting-auction-b1528823.html|access-date=13 November 2020|work=Independent|archive-date=2 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201102124920/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/news/ed-sheeran-art-painting-auction-b1528823.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Later that month, Sheeran backed footballer [[Marcus Rashford]]'s free school meals campaign and opened his own breakfast club at his [[Notting Hill]] restaurant, Bertie Blossoms. He announced on his Instagram that he provided hot breakfasts for "anyone who is normally entitled to a free school meal or who is struggling in these strange times".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.capitalfm.com/news/ed-sheeran-free-breakfast-school-meals-marcus-rashford/ |title=Ed Sheeran Throws Support Behind Marcus Rashford's Free School Meals Campaign & Opens Breakfast Club |work=[[Capital (radio network)|Capital FM]] |access-date=13 November 2020 |archive-date=3 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201103200226/https://www.capitalfm.com/news/ed-sheeran-free-breakfast-school-meals-marcus-rashford/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Sheeran's charity, the Framlingham Foundation Trust, is reported to have donated money to give a primary school teacher to take an imperative course to help children create songs with untraditional instruments which will benefit children with learning difficulties.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran's heartwarming gesture to school teacher and kids with learning disabilities |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/ed-sheerans-heartwarming-gesture-school-22940473 |first=Susan |last=Knox |orig-date=1 November 2020 |date=2 November 2020 |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]] |access-date=13 November 2020 |archive-date=15 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201115003413/https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/ed-sheerans-heartwarming-gesture-school-22940473 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Acting===
Sheeran made his acting debut in 2014, a cameo role as himself on New Zealand soap opera ''[[Shortland Street]]'', filmed while he was in the country for a one-off performance.<ref name=shortland/> In May 2015, he appeared as himself and performed on a live episode of the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[Undateable]]''.<ref name=undateable/> Later that year, while in Australia, he recorded scenes for the soap ''[[Home and Away]]'', as a character based on himself.<ref name="HomeAway">{{cite news |title=Meet 'Teddy': Ed Sheeran appears in Home and Away |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/ed-sheeran-appears-in-home-and-away/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/ed-sheeran-appears-in-home-and-away/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=28 October 2015 |access-date=9 January 2018}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

After recording a cover version of [[Foy Vance]]'s "[[Make It Rain (Foy Vance song)|Make It Rain]]" for ''[[Sons of Anarchy]]'', Sheeran was cast by creator [[Kurt Sutter]] to play Sir Cormac in the medieval drama ''[[The Bastard Executioner]]'' on [[FX (TV channel)|FX]].<ref name="Execute">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/ed-sheeran-joins-bastard-executioner-811150|title=Ed Sheeran to Recur on Kurt Sutter's 'The Bastard Executioner' (Exclusive)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=9 October 2017|archive-date=17 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117132119/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/ed-sheeran-joins-bastard-executioner-811150|url-status=live}}</ref> Sheeran also appeared as himself in the 2016 film ''[[Bridget Jones's Baby]]'' in a scene where [[Bridget Jones]], played by [[Renée Zellweger]], encounters the singer at the [[Glastonbury Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Young |first=Sage |title=The Ed Sheeran Cameo in Bridget Jones's Diary Proves He Doesn't Take Himself Too Seriously |url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/183894-the-ed-sheeran-cameo-in-bridget-joness-diary-proves-he-doesnt-take-himself-too-seriously |website=Bustle |date=14 September 2016 |access-date=23 September 2017 |archive-date=24 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093913/https://www.bustle.com/articles/183894-the-ed-sheeran-cameo-in-bridget-joness-diary-proves-he-doesnt-take-himself-too-seriously |url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 2017, Sheeran appeared in a scene on ''[[Game of Thrones season 7|Game of Thrones]]'' opposite [[Maisie Williams]], who plays [[Arya Stark]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://people.com/tv/game-of-thrones-musician-cameo-shocks-fans/ |title=Ed Sheeran Makes a Surprise Cameo in Game of Thrones Premiere – and Fans Are Going Nuts |date=17 July 2017 |work=People.com |access-date=10 August 2017 |archive-date=10 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810170909/http://people.com/tv/game-of-thrones-musician-cameo-shocks-fans/ |url-status=live }}</ref> [[David Benioff]] explained that since Williams was a big fan of the singer, they wanted to have Sheeran appear on the show to surprise Williams, and that they had tried to get him on for years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/game-of-thrones-season-7-episode-1-ed-sheeran-cameo-s07e01-dragonstone-a7844406.html |title=Game of Thrones fans angry as Ed Sheeran makes painfully unsubtle cameo |date=17 July 2017 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |location=London |access-date=17 July 2017 |archive-date=17 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717234545/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/game-of-thrones-season-7-episode-1-ed-sheeran-cameo-s07e01-dragonstone-a7844406.html |url-status=live }}</ref> It received a mix of positive and very negative reviews.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7866309/ed-sheeran-deletes-twitter-account-game-of-thrones |title=Ed Sheeran Deletes Twitter Account |last=Stutz |first=Colin |date=17 July 2017 |magazine=Billboard |access-date=17 July 2017 |archive-date=18 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170718035316/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7866309/ed-sheeran-deletes-twitter-account-game-of-thrones |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2017/07/17/yes-ed-sheerans-game-of-thrones-cameo-was-a-mistake/ |title=Yes, Ed Sheeran's 'Game of Thrones' Cameo Was A Mistake |last=Tassi |first=Paul |work=Forbes |access-date=14 August 2017 |archive-date=14 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814230224/https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2017/07/17/yes-ed-sheerans-game-of-thrones-cameo-was-a-mistake/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In June 2019, Sheeran made his debut appearance in an advertisement for [[Heinz Tomato Ketchup]].<ref name="Heinz">{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran makes his debut in Heinz Ketchup advert and it's not as cringe as you'd expect |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/06/17/ed-sheeran-makes-debut-heinz-ketchup-not-cringe-expect-9991604/ |access-date=7 July 2019 |work=Metro |archive-date=7 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707160233/https://metro.co.uk/2019/06/17/ed-sheeran-makes-debut-heinz-ketchup-not-cringe-expect-9991604/ |url-status=live }}</ref> A lifelong fan of the product—he has it with everything from [[fish and chips]] to his morning [[Sausage sandwich#United Kingdom|sausage "butty"]] to upmarket dinners, carries a bottle on tour, and has a Heinz Ketchup tattoo on his arm—he put forward an idea he had written for their next TV campaign, and the company responded.<ref name="Heinz"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran: Reiventing Pop music |url=http://restlessnationradio.com/ed-sheeran-reinventing-pop-music/ |access-date=10 July 2019 |work=Restless Nation Radio |archive-date=10 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710083649/http://restlessnationradio.com/ed-sheeran-reinventing-pop-music/ |url-status=live }}</ref> A representative from Heinz stated that "1/3 of @HEINZ Instagram posts include people mentioning or tagging Ed, dating all the way back to 2014."<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran Teams Up with Heinz Ketchup to Create 'Edchup' |url=https://people.com/food/ed-sheeran-heinz-ketchup-edchup/ |access-date=7 July 2019 |work=People.com |archive-date=7 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707161413/https://people.com/food/ed-sheeran-heinz-ketchup-edchup/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Poking fun at people who turn their nose up at those who ask for ketchup in fancy restaurants, the advert sees him walking into a "super posh" restaurant while narrating the message he had sent to the company. As the other wealthy diners look on in horror at the sight of a ketchup bottle, he flips the bottle, bangs it against his hand to budge the ketchup and smothers it all over his food. The company released a limited edition ketchup product known as Ed Sheeran X Heinz ketchup, also known as "Heinz Edchup".<ref name="Heinz"/>

Released in June 2019, Sheeran appeared as himself in a supporting role in the [[Richard Curtis]]/[[Danny Boyle]] film ''[[Yesterday (2019 film)|Yesterday]]'', a film about a struggling singer-songwriter who wakes up to find that no one but he remembers [[the Beatles]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Anne |title='Yesterday': Ed Sheeran's Smart Casting Advice Saved Danny Boyle's Beatles Rom-Com |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/yesterday-ed-sheeran-danny-boyle-beatles-1202153594/ |website=[[IndieWire]] |access-date=2 July 2019 |date=2 July 2019 |archive-date=3 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703130425/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/yesterday-ed-sheeran-danny-boyle-beatles-1202153594/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Impact==
[[File:Ed Sheeran Helsinki 2022 06.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Sheeran concert in Helsinki, August 2022. He had the [[List of highest-grossing concert tours#2010s|highest-grossing tour of the 2010s]], while his current tour, +–=÷x Tour, ranks among the [[List of highest-grossing concert tours#2020s|highest-grossing of the 2020s]].]]
Music journalist [[Alexis Petridis]] has stated that Ed Sheeran "brought pop back down to earth" with his music style, introducing himself "touting an even more austere version of [[Coldplay]]'s dressed-down authenticity: one unassuming man, his guitar and a [[Live looping|loop pedal]]". Noting him as "one of the most influential" artists of his generation, as he spawned "endless imitators", Petridis remarked that the music charts were "packed with Sheeran-alikes" after ''[[x (Ed Sheeran album)|×]]'', describing it as "the wave of earnest, dressed-down, boy-next-door [[troubadour]]s" that reached critical mass.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20210302060726/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/nov/18/how-ed-sheeran-brought-pop-back-down-to-earth|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/nov/18/how-ed-sheeran-brought-pop-back-down-to-earth|title=Grounded: how Ed Sheeran brought pop back down to earth|work=The Guardian|first=Alex|last=Petridis|archivedate=2 March 2021|date=18 November 2019|accessdate=5 March 2022}}</ref> Similarly, ''[[The Guardian]]'' writer Laura Snapes cited him as "the godfather of the current crop of singer-songwriters" in 2019, stating that Sheeran inspired "troubadours" to enter the music charts, and marked "the calcification of the everyman male pop star", and the end of record labels marketing them "exclusively to teenage girls and their mums."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/mar/15/ordinary-boys-ed-sheeran-inspired-troubadours-swept-charts|title=The ordinary boys: how Ed Sheeran-inspired troubadours swept the charts|work=The Guardian|first=Snapes|last=Laura|date=15 March 2019|accessdate=5 March 2022|archive-date=5 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220305084126/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/mar/15/ordinary-boys-ed-sheeran-inspired-troubadours-swept-charts|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' writer Jason Lipshutz noticed that his appeal and performance style had influenced up-and-coming soloists, impacting "a significant number of pop artists who crave his type of singular success."<ref name="bb">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/ed-sheeran-influencing-pop-shawn-mendes-cody-simpson-6473105/|title=The Sheeran Effect: Observing The Beginnings of Ed Sheeran's Influence on Pop|magazine=Billboard|first=Jason|last=Lipshutz|date=17 February 2015|accessdate=5 March 2022|archive-date=4 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220304090457/https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/ed-sheeran-influencing-pop-shawn-mendes-cody-simpson-6473105/|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''[[Financial Times]]'' considered that the scale of Sheeran's commercial accomplishments has "broken through to such a wide and lucrative extent, far beyond the achievements of any of the other singer-songwriters in the market" in the UK.<ref name="financial times">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20201030183655/https://www.ft.com/content/0b124842-856a-11e4-ab4e-00144feabdc0|url=https://www.ft.com/content/0b124842-856a-11e4-ab4e-00144feabdc0|title=The business of being Ed Sheeran|work=Financial Times|first=Craig|last=McLean|archivedate=30 October 2020|date=19 December 2014|accessdate=5 March 2022}}</ref>

[[iHeartMedia]] senior executive Sharon Dastur declared that Sheeran's success has allowed newer artists to be given an opportunity in the mainstream scene with quieter material at the forefront, instead of dance music.<ref name="bb"/> ''[[GQ]]''{{'}}s George Chesterton deemed Sheeran "the de facto voice of a generation" as a consequence of his music reflecting his personality and "the defining characteristics of his audience", with such recurring qualities of his discography corresponding "with those that his own generation, the [[millennials]], most value: authenticity, realness, earnestness, sincerity."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/ed-sheeran-new-album-divide|title=How Ed Sheeran became the biggest male popstar on the planet|work=GQ|first=George|last=Chesterton|date=2 February 2017|accessdate=5 March 2022|archive-date=24 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220124024832/https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/ed-sheeran-new-album-divide|url-status=live}}</ref> [[BBC Radio 1]] executive George Ergatoudis has stated that his "lyrical candour" and his "professional hunger" resonated with younger listeners, giving him a "very clear edge" to breakthrough in a music industry that is "saturated with singer-songwriters", while Sheeran's "niche combination" has made him able to perform at hip-hop, grime and underground events and "convince the urban crowd that he was authentic".<ref name="financial times"/> According to ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'', Sheeran has reached "global pop culture ubiquity".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/5/1/15050000/ed-sheeran-superstar-explained|title=How Ed Sheeran perfected the art of being a mainstream misfit|work=Vox|first=Annie|last=Zaleski|date=1 May 2017|accessdate=5 March 2022|archive-date=4 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220304090820/https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/5/1/15050000/ed-sheeran-superstar-explained|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, the [[BBC]] named him the second-best performing artist of the decade, after [[Adele]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5dNKlNvjbkPPFZffRprwDtH/9-songs-you-probably-didnt-know-ed-sheeran-had-written-for-other-people|title=9 songs you probably didn't know Ed Sheeran had written for other people|work=BBC|date=17 December 2017|accessdate=5 March 2022|archive-date=5 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220305085628/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5dNKlNvjbkPPFZffRprwDtH/9-songs-you-probably-didnt-know-ed-sheeran-had-written-for-other-people|url-status=live}}</ref> while in 2021, ''[[The Independent]]'' said he had "one of the biggest pop careers of this generation."<ref>{{cite news|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20211102121535/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/ed-sheeran-equals-album-b1947159.html|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/ed-sheeran-equals-album-b1947159.html|title=Divide and conquer: how Ed Sheeran took over the world|work=The Independent|first=Anabel|last=Nungent|archivedate=2 November 2021|date=29 October 2021|accessdate=5 March 2022}}</ref> ''Billboard'',<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/ed-sheeran-elton-john-documentary-clip-8095459/|title=Ed Sheeran 'Eternally Jealous' of Elton John's 'Lion King' Music: Watch a Clip From 'The Nation's Favorite Song'|magazine=Billboard|first=Julia|last=Marzovilla|date=22 January 2018|accessdate=5 March 2022|archive-date=4 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220304093807/https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/ed-sheeran-elton-john-documentary-clip-8095459/|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/entertainment/game-of-thrones-season-7-ed-sheeran-debut-got-premiere-maisie-williams-arya-stark-shape-of-you/767290/|title=Game of Thrones season 7: Music icon Ed Sheeran makes delightful debut in premiere|work=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]|date=17 July 2017|accessdate=5 March 2022|archive-date=4 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220304093809/https://www.financialexpress.com/entertainment/game-of-thrones-season-7-ed-sheeran-debut-got-premiere-maisie-williams-arya-stark-shape-of-you/767290/|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Brandon Sun]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brandonsun.com/local/six-year-old-thrilled-to-meet-ed-sheeran-499599941.html|title=Six-year-old thrilled to meet Ed Sheeran|work=[[Brandon Sun]]|first=Melissa|last=Verge|date=5 November 2018|accessdate=5 March 2022|archive-date=4 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220304101754/https://www.brandonsun.com/local/six-year-old-thrilled-to-meet-ed-sheeran-499599941.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and ''[[Arab News]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1727861/lifestyle|title=British pop icon Ed Sheeran welcomes first child|work=[[Arab News]]|date=1 September 2020|accessdate=5 March 2022|archive-date=4 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220304093809/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1727861/lifestyle|url-status=live}}</ref> have cited him as a "British music icon". In a 2023 poll conducted by the [[O2 (UK)|O<sub>2</sub>]] Priority Tickets platform on what musical acts, past and present, music fans would most want to see live, Sheeran ranked third, after [[Queen (band)|Queen]] and the Beatles.<ref>{{cite news |title=Queen tops poll of artists Brits would love to see live |url=https://virginradio.co.uk/music/104340/queen-tops-poll-of-artists-brits-would-love-to-see-live |access-date=24 November 2023 |publisher=Virgin Radio |archive-date=24 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231124030926/https://virginradio.co.uk/music/104340/queen-tops-poll-of-artists-brits-would-love-to-see-live |url-status=live }}</ref> Sheeran and his work have influenced various recording artists, including [[Shawn Mendes]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mtv.co.uk/news/f6l01u/mtv-meets-shawn-mendes|work=MTV|title=MTV Meets: Shawn Mendes|first=Jennifer|last=Lynn|date=2 September 2014|access-date=27 September 2015|archive-date=5 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505042109/http://www.mtv.co.uk/shawn-mendes/news/mtv-meets-shawn-mendes|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Louis Tomlinson]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a345784/one-direction-name-debut-album-up-all-night-reveal-cover.html |title=One Direction name debut album 'Up All Night', reveal cover |work=[[Digital Spy]] |date=16 October 2011 |access-date=21 March 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218110917/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a345784/one-direction-name-debut-album-up-all-night-reveal-cover.html |archive-date=18 February 2012}}</ref> [[Camila Cabello]]<ref name="the new york times">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/11/arts/music/camila-cabello-fifth-harmony-solo-album.html |title=How Camila Cabello Lost Some Friends and Found Her Voice |last=Ugwu |first=Reggie |date=11 January 2018 |work=The New York Times |access-date=13 January 2018 |archive-date=15 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201215121638/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/11/arts/music/camila-cabello-fifth-harmony-solo-album.html |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Cody Simpson]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6473105/ed-sheeran-influencing-pop-shawn-mendes-cody-simpson|title=The Sheeran Effect: Observing The Beginnings of Ed Sheeran's Influence on Pop|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=17 February 2015|access-date=14 November 2020|archive-date=13 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413200135/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6473105/ed-sheeran-influencing-pop-shawn-mendes-cody-simpson|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Accolades==
{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Ed Sheeran}}
On 19 October 2015, Sheeran received an honorary degree from the [[University of Suffolk]] in Ipswich for his "outstanding contribution to music".<ref name="degree"/> Sheeran commented: "Suffolk is very much where I call home. Receiving this recognition is a real privilege."<ref name="degree">{{cite news|title=Ed Sheeran returns home for honorary degree|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-34573628|work=[[BBC News]]|date=20 September 2015|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=8 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220408154101/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-34573628|url-status=live}}</ref> He was appointed [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the [[2017 Birthday Honours]] for "services to music and charity".<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61962|supp=y|page=B22|date=17 June 2017}}</ref> Sheeran received the award from [[Prince Charles]] at [[Buckingham Palace]] on 7 December 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran picks up MBE from Prince Charles at Buckingham Palace |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-42267515 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=7 December 2017 |access-date=27 August 2022 |archive-date=15 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220815103554/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-42267515 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2012, he was named a [[baron]] of [[Principality of Sealand|Sealand]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Amos |first=Thomas |title=How To Become A Baron Or Baroness – Principality Of Sealand |url=https://sealandgov.org/become-a-baron-or-baroness/ |access-date=25 June 2020 |website=Sealand.gov.org |archive-date=27 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200627024820/https://sealandgov.org/become-a-baron-or-baroness/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In addition to having the [[List of highest-grossing concert tours|highest-grossing concert tour]] and being one of the [[List of best-selling music artists|world's best-selling music artists]] with more than 150 million records sold, Sheeran has received a number of awards. As of 2019, he has received four [[Grammy Awards]] (including [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] in 2016 for "Thinking Out Loud"), five [[Brit Awards]] (including [[Brit Award for British Male Solo Artist|British Male Solo Artist]] in 2015), and six [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]] (including [[Billboard Music Award for Top Artist|Top Artist]] in 2018).<ref name="Brits 2015"/><ref name="Grammys 2016"/><ref name="Billboard 2018"/> In 2015 and 2018, he received the [[Ivor Novello Awards|Ivor Novello Award]] for Songwriter of the Year from the [[British Academy of Songwriters, Composers, and Authors]].<ref name="Novello"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran Named Songwriter of the Year at U.K.'s Ivor Novello Awards |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8458811/ed-sheeran-songwriter-of-the-year-uk-ivor-novello-awards |access-date=28 August 2019 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=28 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828085511/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8458811/ed-sheeran-songwriter-of-the-year-uk-ivor-novello-awards |url-status=live }}</ref>

Although he regards Suffolk as home having moved to the county as a young child, Sheeran was recognised by his county of birth in a 2018 poll when he was ranked the fourth-greatest Yorkshireman ever behind [[Monty Python]] comedian [[Michael Palin]], and actors [[Sean Bean]] and [[Patrick Stewart]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Palin named greatest ever Yorkshireman, according to poll|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/michael-palin-yorkshire-greatest-poll-yorkshireman-yorkshire-britons-a8471641.html|access-date=23 October 2022|work=The Independent|archive-date=23 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221023164450/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/michael-palin-yorkshire-greatest-poll-yorkshireman-yorkshire-britons-a8471641.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2024 he won a [[Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|Primetime Creative Arts Emmy]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Original Music and Lyrics|Outstanding Original Music and Lyrics]] for "A Beautiful Game" from ''[[Ted Lasso]]''.

==Personal life==
[[File:Ed Sheeran (8507714431).jpg|thumb|upright|right|Sheeran's tattoos are either connected to his family, achievements, or memories.]]
In early 2011, after securing recording and publishing deals, Sheeran purchased and renovated a farm near [[Framlingham]], Suffolk, where he was raised. He has stated that he hopes to raise a family there.<ref name="Telegraph-McLean"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/114582/Ed-Sheeran-Is-Renovating-A-House-For-His-Future-Family |title=Ed Sheeran Is Renovating A House For His Future Family |publisher=Entertainmentwise |date=13 May 2013 |access-date=8 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618003537/http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/114582/Ed-Sheeran-Is-Renovating-A-House-For-His-Future-Family |archive-date=18 June 2013 }}</ref> During 2013, he lived between [[Hendersonville, Tennessee]]<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Adam |last=Gold |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/ed-sheeran-im-hoping-to-release-three-albums-in-three-years-84093/ |title=Ed Sheeran: 'I'm hoping to Release Three Albums in Three Years' |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=6 September 2013 |access-date=12 August 2020 |archive-date=12 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201112013427/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/ed-sheeran-im-hoping-to-release-three-albums-in-three-years-84093/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and Los Angeles, California.<ref name="elvisduran1">{{cite web|url=http://www.elvisduran.com/pages/whatwetalkedabout.html?feed=136656&article=10747382 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130204011046/http://www.elvisduran.com/pages/whatwetalkedabout.html?feed=136656&article=10747382 |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 February 2013 |title=Ed Sheeran Live In-Studio [PHOTOS + VIDEO + LIVE PERFORMANCE&#93; – Elvis Duran and the Morning Show |publisher=Elvisduran.com |date=30 January 2013 |access-date=8 June 2013 }}</ref> In 2014, he bought a house in [[South London]].<ref name="Telegraph-McLean"/>

Sheeran was in a relationship with Scottish singer-songwriter [[Nina Nesbitt]] (who was in his music video for "[[Drunk (Ed Sheeran song)|Drunk]]") in 2012, before breaking up.<ref name="Nesbitt">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/nina-nesbitt-ed-sheeran-wrote-3845502|title=Nina Nesbitt: Ed Sheeran wrote a song about our love life and I'm giving him a miss at T in the Park|work=Daily Record|date=11 July 2014|access-date=16 October 2015|archive-date=8 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008194557/https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/nina-nesbitt-ed-sheeran-wrote-3845502|url-status=live}}</ref> Nesbitt is the subject of Sheeran's songs "Nina" and "[[Photograph (Ed Sheeran song)|Photograph]]", while most of Nesbitt's album, ''[[Peroxide (Nina Nesbitt album)|Peroxide]]'', is about Sheeran.<ref name="Nesbitt"/> In 2014, Sheeran was in a relationship with Athina Andrelos, who works for chef [[Jamie Oliver]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Why Did Ed Sheeran & Athina Andrelos Break Up? |url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/72320-why-did-ed-sheeran-athina-andrelos-break-up-there-are-a-couple-theories-out-there |access-date=27 September 2021 |work=Bustle |archive-date=27 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210927132215/https://www.bustle.com/articles/72320-why-did-ed-sheeran-athina-andrelos-break-up-there-are-a-couple-theories-out-there |url-status=live }}</ref> She is the inspiration of Sheeran's song "[[Thinking Out Loud]]".<ref name="IBT News">{{cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.com.au/ed-sheeran-confirms-split-girlfriend-who-inspired-thinking-out-loud-athina-andrelos-1433690 |title=Ed Sheeran Confirms Split With Girlfriend Who Inspired 'Thinking Out Loud' Athina Andrelos |work=IBT News |date=27 March 2015 |access-date=20 November 2015 |archive-date=21 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121062343/http://www.ibtimes.com.au/ed-sheeran-confirms-split-girlfriend-who-inspired-thinking-out-loud-athina-andrelos-1433690 |url-status=live }}</ref> They broke up in February 2015.<ref name="IBT News"/> He is also close friends with singer-songwriter [[Taylor Swift]]; the pair collaborated on her albums [[Red (Taylor Swift album)|''Red'']] (original and [[Red (Taylor's Version)|re-recorded]] versions) and [[Reputation (Taylor Swift album)|''Reputation'']], as well as on a remix of the song "[[The Joker and the Queen]]" from Sheeran's album [[= (album)|''='']].<ref name="Clapton"/><ref>{{cite web |date=26 February 2022 |title="The "Joker and the Queen" feat. Taylor Swift is, no-joke, an incredible love song |url=https://georgetownvoice.com/2022/02/26/the-joker-and-the-queen-feat-taylor-swift-is-no-joke-an-incredible-love-song/ |access-date=6 March 2022 |website=The Georgetown Voice |archive-date=6 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220306090610/https://georgetownvoice.com/2022/02/26/the-joker-and-the-queen-feat-taylor-swift-is-no-joke-an-incredible-love-song/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 2015, Sheeran began a relationship with childhood friend and former secondary school classmate Cherry Seaborn.<ref name="Relationship">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-45329646 |title=Ed Sheeran strongly hints that he got married in secret |work=[[BBC News]] |date=28 August 2018 |access-date=16 September 2018 |archive-date=29 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829223302/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-45329646 |url-status=live }}</ref> They announced their engagement in January 2018 and were married a year later.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/42759062/ed-sheeran-engaged-to-long-time-girlfriend-cherry-seaborn |title=Ed Sheeran engaged to long-time girlfriend Cherry Seaborn |date=20 January 2018 |website=BBC Newsbeat |access-date=27 August 2022 |archive-date=20 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120143216/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/42759062/ed-sheeran-engaged-to-long-time-girlfriend-cherry-seaborn |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/ed-sheeran-reveals-date-of-secret-wedding-in-video-featuring-wife-11893798|title=Ed Sheeran reveals date of secret wedding in video featuring wife|publisher=Sky News|date=23 December 2019|access-date=23 December 2019|archive-date=23 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223152037/https://news.sky.com/story/ed-sheeran-reveals-date-of-secret-wedding-in-video-featuring-wife-11893798|url-status=live}}</ref> She is the inspiration of the song "[[Perfect (Ed Sheeran song)|Perfect]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://agreeagain.com/celebrity/edsheeran-cherry-perfect/ |title=How Ed Sheeran wrote "Perfect" for fiancée Cherry Seaborn |date=23 June 2018 |website=Agreeagain |access-date=27 August 2022 |archive-date=21 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220621155031/https://agreeagain.com/celebrity/edsheeran-cherry-perfect/ |url-status=live }}</ref> It was reported on 12 August 2020 that the couple were expecting their first child.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/1321660/ed-sheeran-wife-cherry-seaborn-baby-marriage-children-lockdown-news-latest-updates |title=Ed Sheeran and wife Cherry Seaborn 'expecting first baby' in lockdown announcement |first=Michelle |last=Marshall |date=11 August 2020 |newspaper=[[Daily Express]] |access-date=15 August 2020 |archive-date=14 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200814215822/https://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/1321660/ed-sheeran-wife-cherry-seaborn-baby-marriage-children-lockdown-news-latest-updates |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.ok.co.uk/celebrity-news/breaking-ed-sheeran-wife-pregnant-22506398 |title=Ed Sheeran and wife Cherry Seaborn are 'expecting first child together' |first=Amy |last=Denman |date=11 August 2020 |magazine=OK! |access-date=15 August 2020 |archive-date=12 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200812162335/https://www.ok.co.uk/celebrity-news/breaking-ed-sheeran-wife-pregnant-22506398 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 September, Sheeran announced on Instagram that Seaborn had given birth to a baby girl the previous week.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ed Sheeran on Instagram: "Ello! A quick message from me as I have some personal news that I wanted to share with you... Last week, with the help of an amazing…"|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/CEliNEOBw3O/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/iarchive/instagram/teddysphotos/2388465608854801870 |archive-date=23 December 2021 |url-access=subscription|access-date=1 September 2020|website=Instagram}}{{cbignore}}</ref> On 19 May 2022, it was announced that the couple's second child, a girl, was born.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Aniftos |first=Rania |date=19 May 2022 |title=Ed Sheeran & Cherry Seaborn Welcome Baby Girl: 'We Are Both So in Love With Her' |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/ed-sheeran-cherry-seaborn-welcome-daughter-2-1235073504/ |access-date=19 May 2022 |magazine=Billboard |archive-date=19 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220519221725/https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/ed-sheeran-cherry-seaborn-welcome-daughter-2-1235073504/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Sheeran is a supporter of his local football club [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Ipswich fan Ed Sheeran swearily photobombing Norwich City legends at East Anglia derby will make your day |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/row-zed/ipswich-fan-ed-sheerans-swearily-9926539 |access-date=16 September 2018 |work=The Mirror |archive-date=16 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916164255/https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/row-zed/ipswich-fan-ed-sheerans-swearily-9926539 |url-status=live }}</ref> and his [[+–=÷x Tour]] kit sponsored their [[2021–22 Ipswich Town F.C. season|2021–22 season]].<ref>{{cite web|date=6 May 2021|title=Ipswich shirts to be sponsored by Ed Sheeran next season|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/may/06/ed-sheeran-to-sponsor-ipswich-shirts-next-season|access-date=10 May 2021|website=The Guardian|archive-date=10 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210510062203/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/may/06/ed-sheeran-to-sponsor-ipswich-shirts-next-season|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, Sheeran was named in the club's squad list and given the squad number of 17.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-suffolk-58121177 |title=Ed Sheeran named in Ipswich Town squad list and given number 17 |date=6 August 2021 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=8 August 2021 |archive-date=8 August 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210808003934/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-suffolk-58121177 |url-status=live }}</ref> His [[+–=÷x Tour]] kit sponsorship deal with Ipswich Town was renewed for the [[2022–23 Ipswich Town F.C. season|2022–23 season]].<ref>{{cite news |date=9 June 2022 |title=Ed Sheeran renews Ipswich Town Football Club sponsorship deal |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-suffolk-61744993 |access-date=28 August 2022 |archive-date=28 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220828010308/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-suffolk-61744993 |url-status=live }}</ref> A collector of [[Panini Group|Panini]]'s [[FIFA World Cup]] [[sticker album]], he completed the 2014 World Cup album.<ref>{{cite news |title=Watch: Got, Got, Need! The Story of Panini Stickers – a FourFourTwo Films exclusive |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/watch-got-got-need-story-panini-stickers-a-fourfourtwo-films-exclusive |access-date=16 September 2018 |work=FourFourTwo |archive-date=16 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916164227/https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/watch-got-got-need-story-panini-stickers-a-fourfourtwo-films-exclusive |url-status=live }}</ref> Appearing as a guest on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' on 7 May 2017, Sheeran chose ''[[His Dark Materials]]'' by [[Philip Pullman]] as his book of choice, and a lifetime supply of [[ketchup]] as the one inanimate [[Luxury goods|luxury item]] that he would take with him on a desert island.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08pddvs |title=Ed Sheeran, Desert Island Discs |publisher=[[BBC Radio 4]] |date=7 May 2017 |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322071554/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08pddvs |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2024 Sheeran acquired a minority stake in the club, amounting to 1.4%.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Singer Ed Sheeran has bought a stake in a Premier League club. |url=https://bookmaker-ratings.ru/news/pevets-e-d-shiran-kupil-dolyu-v-klube-apl/ |access-date=August 16, 2024 |website=[[The Bookmaker Ratings]]}}</ref>

In June 2015, ''[[Forbes]]'' listed his earnings at $57&nbsp;million for the previous 12 months, and ranked him the 27th-highest-earning celebrity in the world.<ref name="Forbes">{{cite news |title=The World's Highest-Paid Celebrities |url=https://www.forbes.com/celebrities/list/#tab:overall |work=Forbes |date=22 November 2015 |access-date=27 August 2022 |archive-date=18 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518033904/http://www.forbes.com/celebrities/list/#tab:overall |url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2018, ''Forbes'' named Sheeran ninth on their list of the highest-paid celebrities.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/celebrity/george-clooney-and-kylie-jenner-among-top-10-highest-earning-celebrities/ar-AAAaFFG|title=George Clooney and Kylie Jenner Among Top 10 Highest-Earning Celebrities|website=msn.com|access-date=17 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510160635/https://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/celebrity/george-clooney-and-kylie-jenner-among-top-10-highest-earning-celebrities/ar-AAAaFFG|archive-date=10 May 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> One of the [[List of music artists by net worth|wealthiest musicians]], according to ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' [[Sunday Times Rich List|Rich List]] of 2019, Sheeran was worth £160 million (US$207 million) as the 17th-richest musician in the UK.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-48204955 |title=Ed Sheeran tops Adele as Stormzy joins Sunday Times Rich List |work=[[BBC News]] |date=9 May 2019 |access-date=9 May 2019 |archive-date=11 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190611175234/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-48204955 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sheeran's net worth is estimated at £300 million in 2023.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thetimes.com/culture/music/article/ed-sheeran-net-worth-sunday-times-rich-list-9rnnlm8hb |title=Ed Sheeran net worth — Sunday Times Rich List 2023|work=[[The Times]] |date=26 January 2024|access-date=8 June 2024}}</ref>

On 24 October 2021, Sheeran tested positive for [[COVID-19]] less than a week before the release of his [[= (album)|fifth album]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/covid-19-ed-sheeran-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-but-says-he-will-gig-from-home-12443608 |title=COVID-19: Ed Sheeran tests positive for coronavirus – but says he will gig from home |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=24 October 2021 |access-date=24 October 2021 |archive-date=24 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211024162935/http://news.sky.com/story/covid-19-ed-sheeran-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-but-says-he-will-gig-from-home-12443608 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 March 2023, he revealed that his wife, while pregnant, had developed a [[neoplasm|tumour]] with "no route to treatment until after the birth".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-64809475|title=Ed Sheeran says wife developed tumour in pregnancy, as he announces new album|publisher=BBC|date=1 March 2023|access-date=2 March 2023|archive-date=2 March 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230302001008/https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-64809475|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Legal issues==
Sheeran has faced accusations of [[plagiarism]] with regards to [[chord progression]] and other elements of his music. However, [[tort]] actions which have reached a jury have all been decided decisively in Sheeran's favour.

In 2017, Sheeran settled out of court over claims his song "Photograph" was a "note-for-note" copy of the chorus in the song "[[Amazing (Matt Cardle song)|Amazing]]" by ''[[X Factor]]'' UK winner [[Matt Cardle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/apr/11/ed-sheeran-20m-dollar-copyright-claim-matt-cardle-x-factor|title=Ed Sheeran may regret Photograph that led to $20m copyright case|date=11 April 2017|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=13 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413195924/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/apr/11/ed-sheeran-20m-dollar-copyright-claim-matt-cardle-x-factor|url-status=live}}</ref> Sheeran later regretted the decision to settle, saying that it was done on the advice of his lawyers who thought the case was "more trouble than it was worth."<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran denies Shape of You copyright claim at High Court trial |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-60648263 |access-date=8 March 2022 |work=BBC News |date=7 March 2022 |archive-date=8 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220308021108/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-60648263 |url-status=live }}</ref> He said he regretted settling the claim not because of the money involved, but because it changed his relationship with the song. He said: "I didn't play 'Photograph' for ages after that. I just stopped playing it. I felt weird about it, it kind of made me feel dirty." He also thought that settling the case opened a floodgate of claims, including the "Shape of You" lawsuit.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/ed-sheeran-shape-of-you-lawsuit-win-b2053945.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220526/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/ed-sheeran-shape-of-you-lawsuit-win-b2053945.html |archive-date=26 May 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Ed Sheeran says he now regrets settling £14m 'Photograph' lawsuit in wake of 'Shape of You' trial win |first=Tom|last=Murray|work=The Independent |date=8 April 2022 }}</ref>

In 2018, legal action was brought against Sheeran, [[Sony Music Publishing|Sony/ATV Music Publishing]] and [[Atlantic Records]] by the estate and heirs of the late producer [[Ed Townsend]], who co-wrote the song "[[Let's Get It On (song)|Let's Get It On]]" with [[Marvin Gaye]]. [[United States district court|US District Judge]] Louis Stanton rejected Sheeran's call in 2019 for dismissal of a legal case accusing him of copying parts of the song in "Thinking Out Loud". Stanton said that a jury should decide but that he found "substantial similarities between several of the two works' musical elements".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-01-04/ed-sheeran-margin-gaye-plagiarism-case-going-to-jury/10685922|work=Australian Broadcasting Commission news|title=Jury to decide whether Ed Sheeran copied Marvin Gaye's Let's Get It On for his 2014 song Thinking Out Loud|date=4 January 2019|access-date=27 August 2022|archive-date=1 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220501034840/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-01-04/ed-sheeran-margin-gaye-plagiarism-case-going-to-jury/10685922|url-status=live}}</ref> A previous case by Townsend's estate was dismissed [[without prejudice]] in February 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kenneally|first=Tim|title=Ed Sheeran Off the Hook in Marvin Gaye Copyright Case (for Now)|url=https://www.thewrap.com/ed-sheeran-off-the-hook-in-marvin-gaye-copyright-case-for-now/|website=The Wrap|access-date=28 June 2018|date=3 February 2017|archive-date=28 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628233614/https://www.thewrap.com/ed-sheeran-off-the-hook-in-marvin-gaye-copyright-case-for-now/|url-status=live}}</ref>

The case, closely followed by those in music and legal circles, went to trial on in New York in April 2023. Sheeran's lawyers argued that while the two songs have similar "building blocks" and a specific [[chord progression]], such features are true for many pop songs, and the jury found in favour of Sheeran with a unanimous verdict.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/02cb9be3-3335-4cad-841a-de89b9fe9cbb |title=Ed Sheeran wins 'Let's Get It On' copyright infringement trial |first1=Joe |last1=Miller |first2= Anna|last2= Nicolaou |work=Financial Times |date=4 May 2023 }}</ref> After winning the trial, Sheeran said: "These chords are common building blocks which were used to create music long before 'Let's Get It On' was written and will be used to create music long after we are all gone."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/ed-sheeran-marvin-gaye-copyright-trial.html |title=Ed Sheeran Won His Copyright Trial. Here's What to Know |work=The New York Times |date=4 May 2023 |first=Ben|last=Sisario }}</ref>

Sheeran was taken also to court in March 2022 for a copyright lawsuit over "Shape of You". Musicians Sami Chokri and Ross O'Donoghue alleged that the song infringed "particular lines and phrases" of their 2015 composition "Oh Why".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2022/mar/04/ed-sheeran-is-a-magpie-who-borrows-ideas-copyright-trial-hears|title=Ed Sheeran is a 'magpie' who 'borrows' ideas, copyright trial hears|website=The Guardian|last=Komami|first=Nadia|date=4 March 2022|access-date=5 March 2022|archive-date=4 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220304230631/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2022/mar/04/ed-sheeran-is-a-magpie-who-borrows-ideas-copyright-trial-hears|url-status=live}}</ref> Sheeran won the case, with [[Antony Zacaroli|Mr Justice Zacaroli]] ruling he "neither deliberately nor subconsciously" copied a phrase from "Oh Why" when writing "Shape of You".<ref>{{cite news |date=6 April 2022 |title=Ed Sheeran wins Shape of You copyright case |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-61006984 |access-date=6 April 2022 |archive-date=6 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220406085712/https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-61006984 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=6 April 2022 |title=Ed Sheeran wins court battle over Shape of You plagiarism accusation |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2022/apr/06/ed-sheeran-wins-court-battle-over-shape-of-you-plagiarism-accusation |access-date=6 April 2022 |website=The Guardian |archive-date=6 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220406092538/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2022/apr/06/ed-sheeran-wins-court-battle-over-shape-of-you-plagiarism-accusation |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Political views==
Sheeran publicly opposed [[Brexit]] (the [[United Kingdom]] leaving the [[European Union]]), and supported "remain". Following the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|June 2016 referendum result]] where the British public voted to leave, Sheeran was among a group of British musicians (which included [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Queen (band)|Queen]] drummer [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]], [[Pink Floyd]] drummer [[Nick Mason]] and [[Damon Albarn]] of [[Blur (band)|Blur]] and [[Gorillaz]]) who signed a letter to then Prime Minister [[Theresa May]], drafted by [[Bob Geldof]] in October 2018, calling for "[[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|a 2nd vote]]". Stating that Brexit will "impact every aspect of the music industry. From touring to sales, to copyright legislation to royalty collation", the letter adds: "We dominate the market and our bands, singers, musicians, writers, producers and engineers work all over Europe and the world and in turn, Europe and the world come to us. Why? Because we are brilliant at it ... [Our music] reaches out, all inclusive, and embraces anyone and everyone. And that truly is what Britain is."<ref>{{cite news |title=UK music stars rail against Brexit in open letter to Theresa May |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/oct/06/uk-musician-warn-botched-brexit |access-date=30 May 2019 |work=The Guardian |archive-date=30 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530104206/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/oct/06/uk-musician-warn-botched-brexit |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2017, Sheeran publicly endorsed the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and then-leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]], while adding that "I'm not Mr Political. I vote the way I feel I should, but won't tell somebody else what to do."<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Sheeran says he is a fan of Jeremy Corbyn: 'He cares about other people' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/ed-sheeran-jeremy-corbyn-politics-music-labour-party-general-election-grammy-awards-nominations-a8103091.html |access-date=15 November 2020 |work=The Independent |archive-date=13 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201113231438/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/ed-sheeran-jeremy-corbyn-politics-music-labour-party-general-election-grammy-awards-nominations-a8103091.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2024, Sheeran endorsed the Labour Party and leader [[Keir Starmer]].

In 2021, Sheeran, along with several other celebrities, urged the [[United States Congress]] to pass the proposed [[Equality Act (United States)|Equality Act]], which would expand the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964|Civil Rights Act]] in order to outlaw discrimination against [[LGBT]] people. Sheeran stated in the open letter that the Act is "essential to protect [...] the most marginalized communities."<ref>{{cite news |last=Meyers |first=Dave |title=Ariana Grande, Pink, Halsey, Taylor Swift, Ed Sheeran, Lady Gaga & more urge Congress to pass the Equality Act |url=https://www.wrmf.com/ariana-grande-pink-halsey-taylor-swift-ed-sheeran-lady-gaga-more-urge-congress-to-pass-the-equality-act/ |access-date=22 June 2021 |work=[[WRMF|WRMF FM]] |date=22 June 2021 |archive-date=8 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220408154115/https://www.wrmf.com/ariana-grande-pink-halsey-taylor-swift-ed-sheeran-lady-gaga-more-urge-congress-to-pass-the-equality-act/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2022, during the [[Russian invasion of Ukraine]], Sheeran expressed support for [[Ukraine]] and participated in the [[Concert for Ukraine]] held at the [[Resorts World Arena]] in [[Birmingham]], England.<ref>{{cite news |date=21 March 2022 |title=Ed Sheeran and Camila Cabello join Ukraine concert line-up |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-60822865 |access-date=28 March 2022 |archive-date=26 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220326200104/https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-60822865 |url-status=live }}</ref>

